{"type":"message","id":"78b816f8","parentId":"31b4f02f","timestamp":"2026-04-06T15:06:09.082Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_hypTYWh2huy32WaRYZAdMI0V|fc_06bccc677d7b11e50169d3cbe0b4788190808f01dcc4ecc15d","toolName":"memory_get","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"text\": \"- 2026-04-04: S4 Asset Research planning reached implementation-ready state after 5 review rounds. Docs created/closed under `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S4\\\\` include architecture/runtime/contracts/schemas/actor docs plus `S4_IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md`, `S4_FOUNDATION_PLAN.md`, `S4_SINGLE_TARGET_PROTOTYPE_PLAN.md`, and `S4_IMPLEMENTATION_CHECKLIST.md`.\\n- 2026-04-04: R5 pre-coding alignment decisions for S4: JSON Schema is the canonical contract source; Python should validate artifacts against JSON Schema via a central helper; boundary launch proof must happen early in foundation; `s4.pack_compiler_dispatch.v1` must include `candidate_set_paths`; foundation/runtime directory substrate must explicitly include `batches/`.\\n- 2026-04-04: Important correction from Lucca: the real materialized S3 pattern lives in `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S3`, including `.py`, contracts, and implementation artifacts. S4 must preserve that same pattern/location rather than defaulting implementation into the repo `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\pipeline`. Future guidance/implementation should anchor to the S3-in-workspace pattern first.\\n- 2026-04-04: OpenClaw auth check confirmed local config currently has `anthropic:default` in `api_key` mode and `openai-codex` in `oauth` mode. For Lucca’s goal of using Anthropic subscription + extra usage, the likely correct OpenClaw auth flow is `openclaw models auth login` choosing `Claude CLI`, since that reuses local Claude CLI account login rather than Anthropic API key billing.\\n- 2026-04-04: Model routing/auth was cleaned up. `agents.defaults.model.primary` was restored to `openai-codex/gpt-5.4` so the main default uses OpenAI Codex OAuth, not `openai` API-key routing. `agents.defaults.models` was reduced to the intended set: `openai-codex/gpt-5.4`, `openai-codex/gpt-5.4-mini`, `claude-cli/claude-sonnet-4-6`, `claude-cli/claude-haiku-4-5`, `claude-cli/claude-opus-4-6`.\\n- 2026-04-04: Important correction reaffirmed from S3 lessons: a B2/S4 agent is only considered materially created when it is officially added in OpenClaw and proven in runtime. Local folders/docs alone do not count. The concrete CLI path was re-confirmed: `openclaw agents add [name] --workspace <dir> --model <id> --non-interactive`, then verify with `openclaw agents list`, then prove a real turn.\\n- 2026-04-04: S4 implementation status advanced substantially. Foundation (Phase 1) was completed and proved, including real boundary wiring in `w3_block2.py`, bootstrap creation, real supervisor-shell launch, checkpoint/status writing, and mirror to B2 checkpoints.\\n- 2026-04-04: S4 Phase 2A single-target prototype was completed using the real target “Hotel Quitandinha” (`architectural_complex`/physical anchor). The pipeline proved the full artifact chain on disk: research intake -> batch manifest -> brief -> candidate set -> evaluated set -> coverage report -> research pack -> sector report -> completion checkpoint.\\n- 2026-04-04: S4 discovery policy was frozen in docs and then implemented in runtime direction: Brave Search should be the primary discovery substrate, Firecrawl should be used mainly for fetch/extraction/fallback, and Playwright should remain fallback-only rather than default browsing substrate. This policy was added to `S4_asset_research_architecture.md`.\\n- 2026-04-04: S4 3A Brave integration was completed. `S4/helpers/research_worker.py` was changed so Brave Search is the primary discovery path and Firecrawl is only fallback. Real run quality was strong (e.g. Library of Congress, Wikipedia, InsideInside, YouTube, etc.), with zero Firecrawl credits spent in the successful Brave-first run.\\n- 2026-04-04: S4 Phase 2A was officially considered complete after a real run produced 9 candidates for the Hotel Quitandinha target, 7/7 schema validations passed, coverage resolved to `partially_covered`, final pack/report were written, and checkpoint mirroring to B2 worked.\\n- 2026-04-04: A new planning doc was created at `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S4\\\\S4_AGENT_MATERIALIZATION_PLAN.md` freezing the next transition from helper-backed pipeline to real OpenClaw actors. It defines M1 = materialize `sm_s4_asset_research` first, then M2 progressive operator materialization.\\n- 2026-04-04: Current active next step with Claude Code is M1 for S4: officially create/materialize `sm_s4_asset_research` as a real OpenClaw agent, then switch `w3_block2.py` from temporary supervisor shell launch to real agent launch, and prove Gate M1 with at least the first dispatch step.\\n- 2026-04-04: Lucca wants continuity between WebChat and Telegram while away. Telegram is currently responding, so a clean handoff prompt/context summary is useful for continuing the same S4 + Claude Code coordination thread externally.\\n- 2026-04-05/06: The full S4 actor materialization arc was completed gate by gate. Gates accepted as satisfied: M1 `sm_s4_asset_research`; M2.1 `op_s4_target_builder`; M2.2 `op_s4_web_investigator`; M2.3 `op_s4_target_research_worker`; M2.4 `op_s4_candidate_evaluator` (first attempt failed due to heuristic fallback, rerun passed with genuine semantic reclassification); M2.5 `op_s4_coverage_analyst`; M2.6 `op_s4_pack_compiler`. Result: all 7 S4 actors (1 supervisor + 6 operators) are materially created as real OpenClaw actors and individually proved.\\n- 2026-04-05/06: Phase 3 (Supervisor Hardening) was approved and proved using Python-orchestrated checkpoint-resume as the official model. `supervisor_shell.py` was promoted from bootstrap helper to deterministic runtime orchestrator for the long chain. Evidence proved: phase checkpoints on disk, deterministic resume, schema gates between phases, failure table behavior, `s4_completed.json` + B2 mirror, and explicit failure path with `s4_failed.json` + B2 mirror.\\n- 2026-04-06: Phase 4 (Multi-target) was accepted as satisfied. The S4 chain processed 35/35 targets from the Quitandinha pilot, generated 249 candidates total, 35 candidate sets, 35 evaluated sets, 35 target coverage entries, 82 scene entries, 76 checkpoints, and a final pack status of `partially_covered`. Coverage distribution was realistic (covered/partial/inspiration/unresolved), and 11 gaps were preserved in the pack. Important nuance: for this multi-target run the research worker actor, although already proven in M2.3, was bypassed operationally in favor of the helper path for robustness with long-path handling.\\n- 2026-04-06: Phase 5A and 5B were implemented in code but not yet formally proven by evidence pack. 5A implemented: structured run summary in `supervisor_shell.py`, worker retry (1x + 5s backoff), timeout tuning, and `duration_seconds` per phase checkpoint. 5B implemented: evaluator parallelism via `ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=5)` while keeping evaluator invocations as real OpenClaw actor calls. A later diagnosis showed OpenClaw lane/queue behavior serializes same-agent calls on the main lane; Tobias decided custom lane should be tried first, with helper/KMS fallback only if that fails. At the time of this memory update, 5A/5B are implemented but not counted as proved.\\n- 2026-04-06: Lucca pushed for an aggressive refactor of the S4 middle path because the current materialized assets were visually unacceptable. Tobias agreed with the premise that the current Brave/textual URL -> textual evaluator -> asset download path is operationally inadequate for visual quality, but insisted the refactor must preserve the valid S4 infrastructure (target_builder, web_investigator, coverage, pack compiler, supervisor/checkpoints/contracts) while replacing the visual retrieval/materialization core.\\n- 2026-04-06: A large proposed refactor emerged: replace the current S4 middle path with a dataset_system-style visual retrieval core using Google Images/Serper, parallel direct image download, pHash dedup, and Gemini Vision evaluation via KMS. The proposal keeps S4 infra solid but replaces the practical core of `research_worker` + textual candidate evaluation + current materializer. Tobias did not approve immediate full replacement as-is; he required guardrails: do not mark legacy path deprecated yet, keep coverage semantics unchanged, reconfirm `s4.asset_materialization_report.v1`, do not delete `candidates/` early, and execute in two waves (narrow validation first, then full 35-target run).\\n- 2026-04-06: The most recent active thread is a possible aggressive S4 core refactor based on copying/adapting proven modules from `dataset_system` into `S4/helpers/shared/` and introducing a new pipeline around `s4_query_generator.py`, `s4_image_collector.py`, `s4_visual_evaluator.py`, and `s4_asset_pipeline.py`. Tobias' latest stance: the direction is promising and may be necessary, but it must be staged with explicit guardrails and narrow validation before replacing the current core across all 35 targets.\\n\",\n  \"path\": \"memory/2026-04-04.md\"\n}"}],"details":{"text":"- 2026-04-04: S4 Asset Research planning reached implementation-ready state after 5 review rounds. Docs created/closed under `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S4\\` include architecture/runtime/contracts/schemas/actor docs plus `S4_IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md`, `S4_FOUNDATION_PLAN.md`, `S4_SINGLE_TARGET_PROTOTYPE_PLAN.md`, and `S4_IMPLEMENTATION_CHECKLIST.md`.\n- 2026-04-04: R5 pre-coding alignment decisions for S4: JSON Schema is the canonical contract source; Python should validate artifacts against JSON Schema via a central helper; boundary launch proof must happen early in foundation; `s4.pack_compiler_dispatch.v1` must include `candidate_set_paths`; foundation/runtime directory substrate must explicitly include `batches/`.\n- 2026-04-04: Important correction from Lucca: the real materialized S3 pattern lives in `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S3`, including `.py`, contracts, and implementation artifacts. S4 must preserve that same pattern/location rather than defaulting implementation into the repo `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\pipeline`. Future guidance/implementation should anchor to the S3-in-workspace pattern first.\n- 2026-04-04: OpenClaw auth check confirmed local config currently has `anthropic:default` in `api_key` mode and `openai-codex` in `oauth` mode. For Lucca’s goal of using Anthropic subscription + extra usage, the likely correct OpenClaw auth flow is `openclaw models auth login` choosing `Claude CLI`, since that reuses local Claude CLI account login rather than Anthropic API key billing.\n- 2026-04-04: Model routing/auth was cleaned up. `agents.defaults.model.primary` was restored to `openai-codex/gpt-5.4` so the main default uses OpenAI Codex OAuth, not `openai` API-key routing. `agents.defaults.models` was reduced to the intended set: `openai-codex/gpt-5.4`, `openai-codex/gpt-5.4-mini`, `claude-cli/claude-sonnet-4-6`, `claude-cli/claude-haiku-4-5`, `claude-cli/claude-opus-4-6`.\n- 2026-04-04: Important correction reaffirmed from S3 lessons: a B2/S4 agent is only considered materially created when it is officially added in OpenClaw and proven in runtime. Local folders/docs alone do not count. The concrete CLI path was re-confirmed: `openclaw agents add [name] --workspace <dir> --model <id> --non-interactive`, then verify with `openclaw agents list`, then prove a real turn.\n- 2026-04-04: S4 implementation status advanced substantially. Foundation (Phase 1) was completed and proved, including real boundary wiring in `w3_block2.py`, bootstrap creation, real supervisor-shell launch, checkpoint/status writing, and mirror to B2 checkpoints.\n- 2026-04-04: S4 Phase 2A single-target prototype was completed using the real target “Hotel Quitandinha” (`architectural_complex`/physical anchor). The pipeline proved the full artifact chain on disk: research intake -> batch manifest -> brief -> candidate set -> evaluated set -> coverage report -> research pack -> sector report -> completion checkpoint.\n- 2026-04-04: S4 discovery policy was frozen in docs and then implemented in runtime direction: Brave Search should be the primary discovery substrate, Firecrawl should be used mainly for fetch/extraction/fallback, and Playwright should remain fallback-only rather than default browsing substrate. This policy was added to `S4_asset_research_architecture.md`.\n- 2026-04-04: S4 3A Brave integration was completed. `S4/helpers/research_worker.py` was changed so Brave Search is the primary discovery path and Firecrawl is only fallback. Real run quality was strong (e.g. Library of Congress, Wikipedia, InsideInside, YouTube, etc.), with zero Firecrawl credits spent in the successful Brave-first run.\n- 2026-04-04: S4 Phase 2A was officially considered complete after a real run produced 9 candidates for the Hotel Quitandinha target, 7/7 schema validations passed, coverage resolved to `partially_covered`, final pack/report were written, and checkpoint mirroring to B2 worked.\n- 2026-04-04: A new planning doc was created at `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S4\\S4_AGENT_MATERIALIZATION_PLAN.md` freezing the next transition from helper-backed pipeline to real OpenClaw actors. It defines M1 = materialize `sm_s4_asset_research` first, then M2 progressive operator materialization.\n- 2026-04-04: Current active next step with Claude Code is M1 for S4: officially create/materialize `sm_s4_asset_research` as a real OpenClaw agent, then switch `w3_block2.py` from temporary supervisor shell launch to real agent launch, and prove Gate M1 with at least the first dispatch step.\n- 2026-04-04: Lucca wants continuity between WebChat and Telegram while away. Telegram is currently responding, so a clean handoff prompt/context summary is useful for continuing the same S4 + Claude Code coordination thread externally.\n- 2026-04-05/06: The full S4 actor materialization arc was completed gate by gate. Gates accepted as satisfied: M1 `sm_s4_asset_research`; M2.1 `op_s4_target_builder`; M2.2 `op_s4_web_investigator`; M2.3 `op_s4_target_research_worker`; M2.4 `op_s4_candidate_evaluator` (first attempt failed due to heuristic fallback, rerun passed with genuine semantic reclassification); M2.5 `op_s4_coverage_analyst`; M2.6 `op_s4_pack_compiler`. Result: all 7 S4 actors (1 supervisor + 6 operators) are materially created as real OpenClaw actors and individually proved.\n- 2026-04-05/06: Phase 3 (Supervisor Hardening) was approved and proved using Python-orchestrated checkpoint-resume as the official model. `supervisor_shell.py` was promoted from bootstrap helper to deterministic runtime orchestrator for the long chain. Evidence proved: phase checkpoints on disk, deterministic resume, schema gates between phases, failure table behavior, `s4_completed.json` + B2 mirror, and explicit failure path with `s4_failed.json` + B2 mirror.\n- 2026-04-06: Phase 4 (Multi-target) was accepted as satisfied. The S4 chain processed 35/35 targets from the Quitandinha pilot, generated 249 candidates total, 35 candidate sets, 35 evaluated sets, 35 target coverage entries, 82 scene entries, 76 checkpoints, and a final pack status of `partially_covered`. Coverage distribution was realistic (covered/partial/inspiration/unresolved), and 11 gaps were preserved in the pack. Important nuance: for this multi-target run the research worker actor, although already proven in M2.3, was bypassed operationally in favor of the helper path for robustness with long-path handling.\n- 2026-04-06: Phase 5A and 5B were implemented in code but not yet formally proven by evidence pack. 5A implemented: structured run summary in `supervisor_shell.py`, worker retry (1x + 5s backoff), timeout tuning, and `duration_seconds` per phase checkpoint. 5B implemented: evaluator parallelism via `ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=5)` while keeping evaluator invocations as real OpenClaw actor calls. A later diagnosis showed OpenClaw lane/queue behavior serializes same-agent calls on the main lane; Tobias decided custom lane should be tried first, with helper/KMS fallback only if that fails. At the time of this memory update, 5A/5B are implemented but not counted as proved.\n- 2026-04-06: Lucca pushed for an aggressive refactor of the S4 middle path because the current materialized assets were visually unacceptable. Tobias agreed with the premise that the current Brave/textual URL -> textual evaluator -> asset download path is operationally inadequate for visual quality, but insisted the refactor must preserve the valid S4 infrastructure (target_builder, web_investigator, coverage, pack compiler, supervisor/checkpoints/contracts) while replacing the visual retrieval/materialization core.\n- 2026-04-06: A large proposed refactor emerged: replace the current S4 middle path with a dataset_system-style visual retrieval core using Google Images/Serper, parallel direct image download, pHash dedup, and Gemini Vision evaluation via KMS. The proposal keeps S4 infra solid but replaces the practical core of `research_worker` + textual candidate evaluation + current materializer. Tobias did not approve immediate full replacement as-is; he required guardrails: do not mark legacy path deprecated yet, keep coverage semantics unchanged, reconfirm `s4.asset_materialization_report.v1`, do not delete `candidates/` early, and execute in two waves (narrow validation first, then full 35-target run).\n- 2026-04-06: The most recent active thread is a possible aggressive S4 core refactor based on copying/adapting proven modules from `dataset_system` into `S4/helpers/shared/` and introducing a new pipeline around `s4_query_generator.py`, `s4_image_collector.py`, `s4_visual_evaluator.py`, and `s4_asset_pipeline.py`. Tobias' latest stance: the direction is promising and may be necessary, but it must be staged with explicit guardrails and narrow validation before replacing the current core across all 35 targets.\n","path":"memory/2026-04-04.md"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775487969051}}
{"type":"message","id":"c1a00512","parentId":"78b816f8","timestamp":"2026-04-06T15:06:33.095Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — lembro.\n\n**Onde parámos, em termos práticos:**\n\n1. **S4 já estava estruturalmente forte**\n   - os **7 actors** estavam materializados e provados\n   - **Phase 3** (hardening + checkpoint-resume) estava aprovada\n   - **Phase 4 multi-target** também estava aprovada e provada\n   - **5A/5B** já existiam em código, mas **ainda não estavam formalmente provadas** por evidence pack  \n   Source: `memory/2026-04-04.md`\n\n2. **O problema novo deixou de ser infra/orquestração**\n   O bottleneck passou a ser **qualidade visual real do asset materialization**.  \n   A conclusão foi: o caminho actual de S4 — muito baseado em discovery textual + evaluator textual + download posterior — está a produzir assets **visualmente insuficientes** para o nível que queremos.  \n   Source: `memory/2026-04-04.md`\n\n3. **A conversa virou para um refactor agressivo do core visual do S4**\n   A direcção que ficou em cima da mesa foi:\n   - manter o que já está bom no S4:\n     - `target_builder`\n     - `web_investigator`\n     - coverage\n     - pack compiler\n     - supervisor/checkpoints/contracts\n   - mas **substituir o miolo prático** de retrieval/materialization por algo mais próximo do `dataset_system`:\n     - geração de queries visuais\n     - colecta directa de imagens\n     - dedup por pHash\n     - avaliação visual com Gemini Vision via KMS\n   Source: `memory/2026-04-04.md`\n\n4. **Mas eu não tinha aprovado replacement cego**\n   A minha posição ficou:\n   - a direcção parece **promissora e talvez necessária**\n   - **não** marcar o caminho legado como deprecated já\n   - **não** mudar sem preservar semântica de coverage\n   - reconfirmar o contract `s4.asset_materialization_report.v1`\n   - **não apagar `candidates/` cedo demais**\n   - executar em **duas waves**:\n     - **Wave 1:** validação narrow\n     - **Wave 2:** só depois o run full de 35 targets  \n   Source: `memory/2026-04-04.md`\n\n5. **Nuance importante que ficou registada**\n   No multi-target, o `research_worker` actor já estava provado como actor real, **mas foi bypassado operacionalmente** em favor do helper path por robustez/long-path handling.  \n   E também detectámos que a tentativa de paralelismo do evaluator em 5B estava a ser limitada por **serialização da mesma lane/queue do agent**.  \n   A decisão pendente era: **testar custom lane primeiro**, e só cair em helper/KMS fallback se isso falhasse.  \n   Source: `memory/2026-04-04.md`\n\n**Resumo brutalmente honesto:**  \nNós **não parámos em “falta provar actor”** nem em “falta fechar supervisor”.  \nParámos em algo mais importante: **o S4 funciona, mas o core visual actual não chega para a qualidade necessária**, então a discussão passou a ser **como refactorar agressivamente o miolo sem deitar fora a infra válida que já conquistámos**.\n\nSe quiseres, o próximo passo mais útil agora é um destes 3:\n\n- **A)** eu estruturo o **plano exacto do refactor em waves**  \n- **B)** eu ajudo a definir o **novo contract do middle path visual**  \n- **C)** eu faço uma **comparação explícita old-core vs dataset-style-core**, com riscos, invariantes e estratégia de migração\n\nSe fosses optimizar para clareza de decisão, eu iria de **C -> B -> A**.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_06eabf5088e8d8890169d3cbe63d7881968a1e8a17ef53bc7b\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":2273,"output":832,"cacheRead":21248,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":24353,"cost":{"input":0.0056825,"output":0.01248,"cacheRead":0.005312,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0234745}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775487969084,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d3cbe279cc8196a33fde9ae8a8db4b"}}
