{"type":"message","id":"d5892a20","parentId":"811eb139","timestamp":"2026-04-06T19:13:30.741Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_E7JhcoPvZkHKvpIKZR1nzvWm|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d405d567c88196bb7ad771178fece6","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced 1 block(s) in C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\AGENTS.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  51 - When you learn a lesson → update AGENTS.md, TOOLS.md, or the relevant skill\n  52 - When you make a mistake → document it so future-you doesn't repeat it\n  53 - For operational/technical questions where you are materially uncertain, do cheap verification first (docs, local status, or cheap research subagent) before answering confidently\n  54 - For research-heavy requests, freely fan out into multiple cheap subagents if that improves answer quality; prefer official docs and recent community evidence, then synthesize centrally\n+ 55 - When a sector is being materialized, do not assume that more actors is always better. If the core of the work needs strong control over paths, artifacts, checkpoints, retries, schema validation, or deterministic orchestration, prefer helper-direct / Python substrate over over-agentizing the middle of the pipeline.\n+ 56 - Distinguish clearly between a **tactical shortcut that currently works** and an **approved reusable pattern**. If something is pragmatic but structurally suboptimal (for example hardcoded keys, temporary fallback logic, or legacy dual-format reads), document it explicitly as temporary and do not let it become precedent by accident.\n+ 57 - Before declaring a new sector “ready” or using it as a template for the next one, capture the reusable patterns, anti-patterns, and removal gates that emerged during implementation.\n  55 - **Text > Brain** 📝\n  56 \n  57 ## Red Lines\n  58 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":55},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775502810699}}
{"type":"message","id":"1dd9d07a","parentId":"d5892a20","timestamp":"2026-04-06T19:13:37.689Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Feito.\n\nActualizei o `AGENTS.md` com as lições processuais mais importantes que saíram do S4:\n\n- **não assumir que mais actors = melhor arquitectura**\n- preferir **helper-direct / substrate determinístico** quando o miolo precisa de forte controlo operacional\n- distinguir explicitamente **atalho táctico** vs **padrão aprovado**\n- antes de usar um sector como template, capturar:\n  - padrões reutilizáveis\n  - anti-patterns\n  - removal gates\n\nIsto ajuda a endurecer o processo para S5/S6 e reduz a chance de repetirmos over-materialization ou normalização acidental de shortcuts.\n\nSe quiseres, o próximo passo depois disso é eu preparar também uma **actualização de skill/checklist local** em formato mais operacional, quase como mini-framework para criação dos próximos sectores.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_06eabf5088e8d8890169d405df376c8196a33b1fc05f4f60dd\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":168,"output":184,"cacheRead":54144,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54496,"cost":{"input":0.00042,"output":0.00276,"cacheRead":0.013536,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.016715999999999998}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775502810742,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d405dbebc081969ed13569f8935b45"}}
