grounded, editorially usable scene kit model.\n+414 \n+415 A practical V1 simplification also applies here:\n+416 - motion should not be treated as an open-ended scene-level planning variable\n+417 - instead, `motion_allowed` should be determined by system policy and injected into the scene context\n+418 - the currently preferred policy is `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`","firstChangedLine":116},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775557441097}}
{"type":"message","id":"b3238894","parentId":"f2500505","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:10.770Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2qWzWddfBsSTxepomcZRGc9h|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db44bc4c8196947386bf26757f1a","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md","edits":[{"oldText":"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\n- `motion_allowed`\n- `motion_budget`\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n","newText":"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\n- `motion_policy`\n- `motion_allowed` (deterministically injected rather than freely authored by the S5 LLM)\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n"},{"oldText":"### 3.3 What exactly should `video_direction_frame` control in V1?\n\nIt is already decided that this artifact should exist.\nWhat remains open is its exact scope.\n\nV1 likely needs it to control:\n- global style posture\n- grounding baseline\n- tonal coherence\n- generation mode allowance\n- budget posture\n\nWhat remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\n","newText":"### 3.3 What exactly should `video_direction_frame` control in V1?\n\nIt is already decided that this artifact should exist.\nWhat remains open is its exact scope.\n\nV1 likely needs it to control:\n- global style posture\n- grounding baseline\n- tonal coherence\n- generation mode allowance\n- budget posture\n- deterministic motion policy\n\nWhat remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\n"},{"oldText":"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\nExamples:\n- timing-use enums per asset family\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\n- highly structured pacing grammars\n","newText":"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\nExamples:\n- timing-use enums per asset family\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\n- highly structured pacing grammars\n- scene-level motion strategy authored freely by the LLM beyond deterministic system policy\n"}]},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md\",\"edits\":[{\"oldText\":\"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\\n- `motion_allowed`\\n- `motion_budget`\\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\\n\",\"newText\":\"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\\n- `motion_policy`\\n- `motion_allowed` (deterministically injected rather than freely authored by the S5 LLM)\\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"### 3.3 What exactly should `video_direction_frame` control in V1?\\n\\nIt is already decided that this artifact should exist.\\nWhat remains open is its exact scope.\\n\\nV1 likely needs it to control:\\n- global style posture\\n- grounding baseline\\n- tonal coherence\\n- generation mode allowance\\n- budget posture\\n\\nWhat remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\\n\",\"newText\":\"### 3.3 What exactly should `video_direction_frame` control in V1?\\n\\nIt is already decided that this artifact should exist.\\nWhat remains open is its exact scope.\\n\\nV1 likely needs it to control:\\n- global style posture\\n- grounding baseline\\n- tonal coherence\\n- generation mode allowance\\n- budget posture\\n- deterministic motion policy\\n\\nWhat remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\\nExamples:\\n- timing-use enums per asset family\\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\\n- highly structured pacing grammars\\n\",\"newText\":\"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\\nExamples:\\n- timing-use enums per asset family\\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\\n- highly structured pacing grammars\\n- scene-level motion strategy authored freely by the LLM beyond deterministic system policy\\n\"}]}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":208,"output":456,"cacheRead":110592,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111256,"cost":{"input":0.0005200000000000001,"output":0.006840000000000001,"cacheRead":0.027648,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.035008}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775557441134,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db43a8d4819687367c07e147bc03"}}
{"type":"message","id":"af587abd","parentId":"b3238894","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:11.134Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_2qWzWddfBsSTxepomcZRGc9h|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db44bc4c8196947386bf26757f1a","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"edit\",\n  \"error\": \"Could not find edits[1] in C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md. The oldText must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"edit","error":"Could not find edits[1] in C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md. The oldText must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines."},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775557451097}}
{"type":"message","id":"fda2694d","parentId":"af587abd","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:16.871Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_O5tyi6aGvTqGkEc1EW1osHCG|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db51a0788196baf95d53d98cbf4f","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md","offset":35,"limit":120},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md\",\"offset\":35,\"limit\":120}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":111343,"output":58,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":111401,"cost":{"input":0.27835750000000004,"output":0.00087,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.2792275}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775557451136,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db4e29348196b1a525604498f5ff"}}
{"type":"message","id":"fb7a2c77","parentId":"fda2694d","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:17.986Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_O5tyi6aGvTqGkEc1EW1osHCG|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db51a0788196baf95d53d98cbf4f","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"- S5 = scene kit design\n- S6 = scene kit materialization\n- S7 = editorial scene resolution / assembly\n\n### 2.2 Central shift in S5\nS5 should not be framed as:\n- prompt writing\n- image picking\n- final scene resolution\n- one-image-per-scene planning\n\nS5 should be framed as:\n- scene kit design\n- asset-space specification per scene\n- controlled balance of grounding and creative freedom\n\n### 2.3 S4 output posture\nS4 outputs are primarily:\n- factual anchors\n- reference inputs\n- anti-hallucination support\n\nThey are not assumed to be preferred final video assets by default.\n\n### 2.4 Global frame requirement\nA global directional artifact is required before scene-level kit specs.\n\nThe conceptual object for this is:\n- `video_direction_frame`\n\n### 2.5 Scene-level boundary object\nThe main scene-level object should now be thought of as:\n- `scene_kit_spec`\n\nnot as a narrowly framed “single-scene production plan.”\n\n### 2.6 Asset families as primitive\nThe internal primitive of the scene kit should be:\n- `asset_families[]`\n\nrather than prematurely rigid one-asset slots.\n\n### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\n- `motion_allowed`\n- `motion_budget`\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n\n### 2.8 V1 simplicity rule\nV1 should remain simpler than the maximum richness theoretically available.\n\nThe boundary should optimize for:\n- stability\n- legibility\n- inspectability\n- downstream usefulness\n\nnot maximum semantic density.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Highest-priority open questions\n\nThe following questions still need disciplined treatment.\n\n---\n\n## 3.1 What is the minimum viable `scene_kit_spec`?\n\nThis is the most important unresolved design question.\n\nThe team still needs to freeze:\n- which fields are essential in V1\n- which should remain free-text\n- which should be constrained enums\n- which should be postponed\n\nThe danger is over-designing too early.\n\n---\n\n## 3.2 What is the minimum viable grammar of `asset_families[]`?\n\nOpen questions include:\n- how many family roles exist in V1\n- how family purpose should be expressed\n- how asset counts should be modeled\n- how grounding vs freedom should be represented\n- how reference inputs should be attached\n\nThis must be strong enough to drive S6 but simple enough to remain consistent.\n\n---\n\n## 3.3 What exactly should `video_direction_frame` control in V1?\n\nIt is already decided that this artifact should exist.\nWhat remains open is its exact scope.\n\nV1 likely needs it to control:\n- global style posture\n- grounding baseline\n- tonal coherence\n- generation mode allowance\n- budget posture\n\nWhat remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\n\n---\n\n## 3.4 How should grounding be expressed at family level?\n\nOpen questions:\n- is `grounding_strength` enough?\n- does the model also need a separate identity-integrity concept per family?\n- should family-level preserve requirements be mandatory or optional?\n- how much reference trace detail is useful at spec time vs delivery time?\n\n---\n\n[172 more lines in file. Use offset=155 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775557457949}}
{"type":"message","id":"c8e3a488","parentId":"fb7a2c77","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:25.618Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_RTdWCVHaJ5ozUlYo0HbVOdcp|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db5591b881968a662b6c0903cb14","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md","edits":[{"oldText":"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\n- `motion_allowed`\n- `motion_budget`\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n","newText":"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\n- `motion_policy`\n- `motion_allowed` (deterministically injected rather than freely authored by the S5 LLM)\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n"},{"oldText":"V1 likely needs it to control:\n- global style posture\n- grounding baseline\n- tonal coherence\n- generation mode allowance\n- budget posture\n","newText":"V1 likely needs it to control:\n- global style posture\n- grounding baseline\n- tonal coherence\n- generation mode allowance\n- budget posture\n- deterministic motion policy\n"},{"oldText":"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\nExamples:\n- timing-use enums per asset family\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\n- highly structured pacing grammars\n","newText":"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\nExamples:\n- timing-use enums per asset family\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\n- highly structured pacing grammars\n- scene-level motion strategy authored freely by the LLM beyond deterministic system policy\n"}]},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md\",\"edits\":[{\"oldText\":\"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\\n- `motion_allowed`\\n- `motion_budget`\\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\\n\",\"newText\":\"### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\\nThe boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\\n- `allowed_generation_modes`\\n- `motion_policy`\\n- `motion_allowed` (deterministically injected rather than freely authored by the S5 LLM)\\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"V1 likely needs it to control:\\n- global style posture\\n- grounding baseline\\n- tonal coherence\\n- generation mode allowance\\n- budget posture\\n\",\"newText\":\"V1 likely needs it to control:\\n- global style posture\\n- grounding baseline\\n- tonal coherence\\n- generation mode allowance\\n- budget posture\\n- deterministic motion policy\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\\nExamples:\\n- timing-use enums per asset family\\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\\n- highly structured pacing grammars\\n\",\"newText\":\"### 4.2 Full editorial rhythm modeling\\nExamples:\\n- timing-use enums per asset family\\n- dense cut-pattern prediction\\n- highly structured pacing grammars\\n- scene-level motion strategy authored freely by the LLM beyond deterministic system policy\\n\"}]}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":861,"output":344,"cacheRead":111232,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112437,"cost":{"input":0.0021525000000000003,"output":0.0051600000000000005,"cacheRead":0.027808,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0351205}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775557457988,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db548a408196ae4047ec5e81cdf8"}}
{"type":"message","id":"11d5c76f","parentId":"c8e3a488","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:24:25.967Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_RTdWCVHaJ5ozUlYo0HbVOdcp|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db5591b881968a662b6c0903cb14","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced 3 block(s) in C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FREEZE_ORDER.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  76 \n  77 ### 2.7 S6 constraint awareness\n  78 The boundary must include practical production constraints such as:\n  79 - `allowed_generation_modes`\n- 80 - `motion_allowed`\n- 81 - `motion_budget`\n+ 80 - `motion_policy`\n+ 81 - `motion_allowed` (deterministically injected rather than freely authored by the S5 LLM)\n  82 - `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n  83 \n  84 ### 2.8 V1 simplicity rule\n  85 V1 should remain simpler than the maximum richness theoretically available.\n     ...\n 137 - grounding baseline\n 138 - tonal coherence\n 139 - generation mode allowance\n 140 - budget posture\n+141 - deterministic motion policy\n 141 \n 142 What remains open is whether anything more is needed at this stage.\n 143 \n 144 ---\n     ...\n 203 Examples:\n 204 - timing-use enums per asset family\n 205 - dense cut-pattern prediction\n 206 - highly structured pacing grammars\n+208 - scene-level motion strategy authored freely by the LLM beyond deterministic system policy\n 207 \n 208 ### 4.3 Final schema hardening\n 209 Examples:\n 210 - final JSON Schema files\n     ...","firstChangedLine":80},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775557465930}}
{"type":"message","id":"98b5acf6","parentId":"11d5c76f","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:25:26.546Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_oIqzs0NvhM4jagbt2qsqGJHn|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db5e26ac81968d10dd1762d02761","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md","content":"# S5 Asset Family Grammar V1 Draft\n\n_Status: conceptual grammar draft_  \n_Last updated: 2026-04-07_  \n_Owner: Tobias_\n\n---\n\n## 1. Purpose of this document\n\nThis document proposes the preferred **V1 grammar** for `asset_families[]` inside the `scene_kit_spec` model.\n\nIts purpose is to move the S5 design from high-level concept into a more operational object grammar without prematurely freezing final schemas.\n\nThis document specifically addresses:\n- which grammar direction should be preferred for V1\n- how `asset_families[]` should be structured\n- how grounding-critical references should be represented\n- how the grammar should support S6 materialization without over-closing S7 editorial freedom\n- how to keep the model implementable and stable in V1\n\nThis draft also incorporates an important simplification:\n\n> motion should not be freely invented by the S5 LLM in V1.\n\nInstead, a deterministic system rule should decide whether motion is allowed for a scene.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Why this grammar matters\n\nThe entire scene-kit model depends on `asset_families[]` being well designed.\n\nIf the grammar is too weak:\n- S6 will not know what kinds of material to produce\n- S7 will receive a shallow or repetitive asset space\n- the scene kit concept will collapse back toward rigid one-image thinking\n\nIf the grammar is too rich:\n- LLM outputs will become inconsistent\n- field usage will drift\n- implementation will become slow and brittle\n- V1 will over-design problems that the system is not ready to solve yet\n\nSo the goal is not maximal richness.\nThe goal is:\n\n> the smallest grammar that can still express a real, grounded, editorially useful scene kit.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Candidate directions considered\n\nTwo directions were considered seriously for V1.\n\n### Option B — role + function\nA family carries:\n- a role\n- a more specific function\n- plus grounding and production fields\n\nThis is compact and expressive, but it tends to overload a single family object with both production and editorial meaning at once.\n\n### Option D — two-layer grammar\nA family carries:\n- a production-facing layer\n- a lightweight editorial-facing layer\n\nThis is slightly more structured, but it separates concerns more cleanly and appears better aligned with the intended S5→S6→S7 chain.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Preferred direction for V1\n\nThe current preferred direction is:\n\n## Option D — two-layer grammar (contained V1 version)\n\nThis means each asset family should contain:\n\n### Layer 1 — production-facing fields\nThese fields are primarily for S5→S6 communication.\nThey define what kind of family this is, how important it is, how grounded it must be, and how it should be materialized.\n\n### Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\nThese fields provide minimal downstream usefulness for S7 without turning V1 into a full editorial grammar.\n\nThis split is attractive because it:\n- keeps S6-facing structure clear\n- preserves a future bridge into S7\n- avoids overloading one field with both production and editorial semantics\n- remains simpler than a fully editorial-first model\n\n---\n\n## 5. Core V1 principle: factual grounding is not optional in factual scenes\n\nA crucial rule must be explicit in this grammar:\n\n> when a scene depicts a real and identifiable person, place, building, city, object, weapon, vehicle, aircraft, artifact, or other factual element, the correct S4 references must be used as grounding inputs for generation.\n\nThis is not a stylistic preference.\nIt is a structural correctness requirement.\n\nThe reason is practical and proven:\n- if the visuals drift away from the real referent\n- viewers notice\n- comments call out the inaccuracy\n- trust degrades\n\nThat means V1 grammar must make room for:\n- `reference_inputs[]`\n- `preserve_requirements[]`\n- grounding strength\n- clear constraints against generic drift\n\nThese fields are not decorative.\nThey are central to the system’s factual integrity.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Proposed V1 grammar\n\nEach `asset_family` should have the following structure.\n\n---\n\n## 6.1 Layer 1 — production-facing fields\n\n### `family_id`\nStable identifier within the scene kit.\n\n### `family_type`\nThe broad type of material this family represents.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `hero`\n- `support`\n- `detail`\n- `atmospheric`\n- `transition`\n- `fallback`\n\nThese values are intentionally modest.\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\n\n### `priority`\nHow important this family is to the scene.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `required`\n- `preferred`\n- `optional`\n\n### `target_asset_count`\nHow many assets this family should ideally yield.\n\nSuggested shape:\n- `minimum`\n- `ideal`\n- `maximum`\n\n### `grounding_strength`\nHow strongly the family must remain anchored to the factual world of the scene.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `high`\n- `medium`\n- `low`\n\n### `creative_freedom_level`\nHow much interpretive freedom S6 may use when materializing this family.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `strict`\n- `controlled`\n- `moderate`\n- `open`\n\n### `preferred_generation_modes[]`\nWhich generation modes best fit this family.\n\nProposed V1 examples:\n- `reference_guided_generation`\n- `regeneration_from_reference`\n- `from_scratch_generation`\n- `multi_reference_synthesis`\n- `motion_generation`\n\nThese should remain under the limits of the active video-level generation policy.\n\n### `reference_inputs[]`\nThe references from S4 or derived reference packages that should feed this family.\n\nThis field is especially important in factual scenes.\n\n### `preserve_requirements[]`\nA short list of what must remain accurate or legible if this family is generated from references.\n\nExamples:\n- facial identity\n- building silhouette\n- vehicle profile\n- object shape\n- period-accurate details\n\n### `avoid_literal_copy_notes[]`\nWhat should explicitly not be copied literally from the references.\n\nExamples:\n- exact source framing\n- source watermark-bearing composition\n- directly recognizable copyrighted layout\n- source-specific visual signature\n\n### `family_notes`\nShort explanatory note for cases where the structured fields are insufficient.\n\n---\n\n## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\n\n### `editorial_affordance`\nA lightweight indicator of how this family is likely to help downstream editorial work.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `hold`\n- `insert`\n- `sequence`\n- `bridge`\n- `contrast`\n\nThese values are intentionally light.\nThey are not a full editorial grammar.\nThey only provide enough signal to help downstream thinking.\n\n### `editorial_notes`\nShort free-text note on how the family is likely to be useful in the cut.\n\nThis is preferable to adding many more enums too early.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Motion simplification for V1\n\nV1 should avoid making motion a free design variable at the LLM level.\n\n### 7.1 Current preferred policy\nThe preferred system-level rule is:\n\n- `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\n- scenes with index `<= 10` receive `motion_allowed = true`\n- scenes after that receive `motion_allowed = false`\n\n### 7.2 Important consequence\nThis means:\n- the S5 LLM does **not** decide motion from scratch\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically by the substrate or boundary logic\n- families may still prefer `motion_generation` only if the policy allows it for that scene\n\n### 7.3 Why this simplification is good\nIt reduces:\n- complexity\n- inconsistency\n- cost explosion\n- unnecessary planner burden\n\nwhile still enabling motion where the system most wants it.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Worked examples\n\nThe examples below are intentionally concrete because the grammar only becomes understandable when seen under real scene conditions.\n\n---\n\n## 8.1 Real person scene\n\n### Scene\nGeorge S. Patton is introduced as the commanding force of an offensive.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f1\nfamily_type: hero\npriority: required\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 2\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\n  - regeneration_from_reference\nreference_inputs:\n  - patton_face_reference_01\n  - patton_uniform_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - facial identity of George S. Patton\n  - correct military uniform cues\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid exact source framing\neditorial_affordance: hold\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt tells S6 very clearly:\n- who the scene must show\n- what cannot drift\n- how free the generation may be\n- what editorial role the output is likely to serve\n\n---\n\n## 8.2 Real building / place scene\n\n### Scene\nHotel Quitandinha appears as a symbol of scale, prestige, and national ambition.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f2\nfamily_type: support\npriority: preferred\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 2\n  ideal: 3\n  maximum: 4\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\nreference_inputs:\n  - quitandinha_facade_01\n  - quitandinha_architecture_detail_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - recognizable Hotel Quitandinha architecture\n  - key facade and structure cues\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\neditorial_affordance: sequence\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nThe family remains grounded in the correct building while still supporting editorial richness.\n\n---\n\n## 8.3 Real equipment / vehicle scene\n\n### Scene\nA Tiger I tank is described as a symbol of German armored power.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f3\nfamily_type: detail\npriority: preferred\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 3\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\nreference_inputs:\n  - tiger1_profile_01\n  - tiger1_turret_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - Tiger I silhouette\n  - correct turret/body structure\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\neditorial_affordance: insert\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt directly encodes the rule that the system must not drift into generic vehicles when factual specificity is essential.\n\n---\n\n## 8.4 Symbolic / evocative scene\n\n### Scene\nAn empire is described as rotting from within.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f4\nfamily_type: atmospheric\npriority: required\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 3\ngrounding_strength: low\ncreative_freedom_level: open\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - from_scratch_generation\n  - multi_reference_synthesis\nreference_inputs:\n  - imperial_hall_reference_01\n  - decay_texture_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - tonal coherence with the rest of the video\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\neditorial_affordance: contrast\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt shows that the same grammar can support scenes where factual identity is less rigid while still preserving coherence.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Why Option D is preferred over Option B\n\nOption B remains a respectable alternative, but the current preference for D is based on the following advantages.\n\n### 9.1 Cleaner separation of concerns\nD separates:\n- what S6 must produce\n- how the family may be useful editorially\n\nThis is better than overloading one role/function pair with both meanings.\n\n### 9.2 Better future bridge into S7\nThe lightweight editorial layer gives a path toward downstream editing without turning V1 into a fully editorial grammar.\n\n### 9.3 Stronger long-term scalability\nD is more likely to age well as the system becomes more sophisticated.\n\n### 9.4 Still simple enough for V1\nAs long as the editorial layer remains light, D does not appear too heavy for V1.\n\n---\n\n## 10. What should remain out of scope for V1\n\nV1 should not yet include:\n- detailed sub-taxonomies for every family type\n- complex timing grammars\n- fine-grained motion strategy per family authored by the LLM\n- deep scene-to-scene editorial logic\n- asset scoring theory inside the grammar itself\n\nThose can be added later if real downstream consumers demand them.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Summary\n\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\n\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\n\nThis grammar is preferred because it:\n- preserves factual grounding where needed\n- supports controlled creative freedom\n- helps S6 materialize useful kits\n- gives S7 a better editorial bridge\n- remains implementable in V1\n\nA further V1 simplification also applies:\n- motion should not be decided freely by the S5 LLM\n- the preferred policy is `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically into the scene context\n\nThis keeps the grammar strong without making it unnecessarily complicated.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md\",\"content\":\"# S5 Asset Family Grammar V1 Draft\\n\\n_Status: conceptual grammar draft_  \\n_Last updated: 2026-04-07_  \\n_Owner: Tobias_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Purpose of this document\\n\\nThis document proposes the preferred **V1 grammar** for `asset_families[]` inside the `scene_kit_spec` model.\\n\\nIts purpose is to move the S5 design from high-level concept into a more operational object grammar without prematurely freezing final schemas.\\n\\nThis document specifically addresses:\\n- which grammar direction should be preferred for V1\\n- how `asset_families[]` should be structured\\n- how grounding-critical references should be represented\\n- how the grammar should support S6 materialization without over-closing S7 editorial freedom\\n- how to keep the model implementable and stable in V1\\n\\nThis draft also incorporates an important simplification:\\n\\n> motion should not be freely invented by the S5 LLM in V1.\\n\\nInstead, a deterministic system rule should decide whether motion is allowed for a scene.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Why this grammar matters\\n\\nThe entire scene-kit model depends on `asset_families[]` being well designed.\\n\\nIf the grammar is too weak:\\n- S6 will not know what kinds of material to produce\\n- S7 will receive a shallow or repetitive asset space\\n- the scene kit concept will collapse back toward rigid one-image thinking\\n\\nIf the grammar is too rich:\\n- LLM outputs will become inconsistent\\n- field usage will drift\\n- implementation will become slow and brittle\\n- V1 will over-design problems that the system is not ready to solve yet\\n\\nSo the goal is not maximal richness.\\nThe goal is:\\n\\n> the smallest grammar that can still express a real, grounded, editorially useful scene kit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Candidate directions considered\\n\\nTwo directions were considered seriously for V1.\\n\\n### Option B — role + function\\nA family carries:\\n- a role\\n- a more specific function\\n- plus grounding and production fields\\n\\nThis is compact and expressive, but it tends to overload a single family object with both production and editorial meaning at once.\\n\\n### Option D — two-layer grammar\\nA family carries:\\n- a production-facing layer\\n- a lightweight editorial-facing layer\\n\\nThis is slightly more structured, but it separates concerns more cleanly and appears better aligned with the intended S5→S6→S7 chain.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Preferred direction for V1\\n\\nThe current preferred direction is:\\n\\n## Option D — two-layer grammar (contained V1 version)\\n\\nThis means each asset family should contain:\\n\\n### Layer 1 — production-facing fields\\nThese fields are primarily for S5→S6 communication.\\nThey define what kind of family this is, how important it is, how grounded it must be, and how it should be materialized.\\n\\n### Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\\nThese fields provide minimal downstream usefulness for S7 without turning V1 into a full editorial grammar.\\n\\nThis split is attractive because it:\\n- keeps S6-facing structure clear\\n- preserves a future bridge into S7\\n- avoids overloading one field with both production and editorial semantics\\n- remains simpler than a fully editorial-first model\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Core V1 principle: factual grounding is not optional in factual scenes\\n\\nA crucial rule must be explicit in this grammar:\\n\\n> when a scene depicts a real and identifiable person, place, building, city, object, weapon, vehicle, aircraft, artifact, or other factual element, the correct S4 references must be used as grounding inputs for generation.\\n\\nThis is not a stylistic preference.\\nIt is a structural correctness requirement.\\n\\nThe reason is practical and proven:\\n- if the visuals drift away from the real referent\\n- viewers notice\\n- comments call out the inaccuracy\\n- trust degrades\\n\\nThat means V1 grammar must make room for:\\n- `reference_inputs[]`\\n- `preserve_requirements[]`\\n- grounding strength\\n- clear constraints against generic drift\\n\\nThese fields are not decorative.\\nThey are central to the system’s factual integrity.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. Proposed V1 grammar\\n\\nEach `asset_family` should have the following structure.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6.1 Layer 1 — production-facing fields\\n\\n### `family_id`\\nStable identifier within the scene kit.\\n\\n### `family_type`\\nThe broad type of material this family represents.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `hero`\\n- `support`\\n- `detail`\\n- `atmospheric`\\n- `transition`\\n- `fallback`\\n\\nThese values are intentionally modest.\\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\\n\\n### `priority`\\nHow important this family is to the scene.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `required`\\n- `preferred`\\n- `optional`\\n\\n### `target_asset_count`\\nHow many assets this family should ideally yield.\\n\\nSuggested shape:\\n- `minimum`\\n- `ideal`\\n- `maximum`\\n\\n### `grounding_strength`\\nHow strongly the family must remain anchored to the factual world of the scene.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `high`\\n- `medium`\\n- `low`\\n\\n### `creative_freedom_level`\\nHow much interpretive freedom S6 may use when materializing this family.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `strict`\\n- `controlled`\\n- `moderate`\\n- `open`\\n\\n### `preferred_generation_modes[]`\\nWhich generation modes best fit this family.\\n\\nProposed V1 examples:\\n- `reference_guided_generation`\\n- `regeneration_from_reference`\\n- `from_scratch_generation`\\n- `multi_reference_synthesis`\\n- `motion_generation`\\n\\nThese should remain under the limits of the active video-level generation policy.\\n\\n### `reference_inputs[]`\\nThe references from S4 or derived reference packages that should feed this family.\\n\\nThis field is especially important in factual scenes.\\n\\n### `preserve_requirements[]`\\nA short list of what must remain accurate or legible if this family is generated from references.\\n\\nExamples:\\n- facial identity\\n- building silhouette\\n- vehicle profile\\n- object shape\\n- period-accurate details\\n\\n### `avoid_literal_copy_notes[]`\\nWhat should explicitly not be copied literally from the references.\\n\\nExamples:\\n- exact source framing\\n- source watermark-bearing composition\\n- directly recognizable copyrighted layout\\n- source-specific visual signature\\n\\n### `family_notes`\\nShort explanatory note for cases where the structured fields are insufficient.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\\n\\n### `editorial_affordance`\\nA lightweight indicator of how this family is likely to help downstream editorial work.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `hold`\\n- `insert`\\n- `sequence`\\n- `bridge`\\n- `contrast`\\n\\nThese values are intentionally light.\\nThey are not a full editorial grammar.\\nThey only provide enough signal to help downstream thinking.\\n\\n### `editorial_notes`\\nShort free-text note on how the family is likely to be useful in the cut.\\n\\nThis is preferable to adding many more enums too early.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7. Motion simplification for V1\\n\\nV1 should avoid making motion a free design variable at the LLM level.\\n\\n### 7.1 Current preferred policy\\nThe preferred system-level rule is:\\n\\n- `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\\n- scenes with index `<= 10` receive `motion_allowed = true`\\n- scenes after that receive `motion_allowed = false`\\n\\n### 7.2 Important consequence\\nThis means:\\n- the S5 LLM does **not** decide motion from scratch\\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically by the substrate or boundary logic\\n- families may still prefer `motion_generation` only if the policy allows it for that scene\\n\\n### 7.3 Why this simplification is good\\nIt reduces:\\n- complexity\\n- inconsistency\\n- cost explosion\\n- unnecessary planner burden\\n\\nwhile still enabling motion where the system most wants it.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8. Worked examples\\n\\nThe examples below are intentionally concrete because the grammar only becomes understandable when seen under real scene conditions.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8.1 Real person scene\\n\\n### Scene\\nGeorge S. Patton is introduced as the commanding force of an offensive.\\n\\n### Example family\\n```yaml\\nfamily_id: f1\\nfamily_type: hero\\npriority: required\\ntarget_asset_count:\\n  minimum: 1\\n  ideal: 2\\n  maximum: 2\\ngrounding_strength: high\\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\\npreferred_generation_modes:\\n  - reference_guided_generation\\n  - regeneration_from_reference\\nreference_inputs:\\n  - patton_face_reference_01\\n  - patton_uniform_reference_02\\npreserve_requirements:\\n  - facial identity of George S. Patton\\n  - correct military uniform cues\\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid exact source framing\\neditorial_affordance: hold\\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene.\\n```\\n\\n### Why this works\\nIt tells S6 very clearly:\\n- who the scene must show\\n- what cannot drift\\n- how free the generation may be\\n- what editorial role the output is likely to serve\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8.2 Real building / place scene\\n\\n### Scene\\nHotel Quitandinha appears as a symbol of scale, prestige, and national ambition.\\n\\n### Example family\\n```yaml\\nfamily_id: f2\\nfamily_type: support\\npriority: preferred\\ntarget_asset_count:\\n  minimum: 2\\n  ideal: 3\\n  maximum: 4\\ngrounding_strength: high\\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\\npreferred_generation_modes:\\n  - reference_guided_generation\\nreference_inputs:\\n  - quitandinha_facade_01\\n  - quitandinha_architecture_detail_02\\npreserve_requirements:\\n  - recognizable Hotel Quitandinha architecture\\n  - key facade and structure cues\\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\\neditorial_affordance: sequence\\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\\n```\\n\\n### Why this works\\nThe family remains grounded in the correct building while still supporting editorial richness.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8.3 Real equipment / vehicle scene\\n\\n### Scene\\nA Tiger I tank is described as a symbol of German armored power.\\n\\n### Example family\\n```yaml\\nfamily_id: f3\\nfamily_type: detail\\npriority: preferred\\ntarget_asset_count:\\n  minimum: 1\\n  ideal: 2\\n  maximum: 3\\ngrounding_strength: high\\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\\npreferred_generation_modes:\\n  - reference_guided_generation\\nreference_inputs:\\n  - tiger1_profile_01\\n  - tiger1_turret_reference_02\\npreserve_requirements:\\n  - Tiger I silhouette\\n  - correct turret/body structure\\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\\neditorial_affordance: insert\\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\\n```\\n\\n### Why this works\\nIt directly encodes the rule that the system must not drift into generic vehicles when factual specificity is essential.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8.4 Symbolic / evocative scene\\n\\n### Scene\\nAn empire is described as rotting from within.\\n\\n### Example family\\n```yaml\\nfamily_id: f4\\nfamily_type: atmospheric\\npriority: required\\ntarget_asset_count:\\n  minimum: 1\\n  ideal: 2\\n  maximum: 3\\ngrounding_strength: low\\ncreative_freedom_level: open\\npreferred_generation_modes:\\n  - from_scratch_generation\\n  - multi_reference_synthesis\\nreference_inputs:\\n  - imperial_hall_reference_01\\n  - decay_texture_reference_02\\npreserve_requirements:\\n  - tonal coherence with the rest of the video\\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\\neditorial_affordance: contrast\\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\\n```\\n\\n### Why this works\\nIt shows that the same grammar can support scenes where factual identity is less rigid while still preserving coherence.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 9. Why Option D is preferred over Option B\\n\\nOption B remains a respectable alternative, but the current preference for D is based on the following advantages.\\n\\n### 9.1 Cleaner separation of concerns\\nD separates:\\n- what S6 must produce\\n- how the family may be useful editorially\\n\\nThis is better than overloading one role/function pair with both meanings.\\n\\n### 9.2 Better future bridge into S7\\nThe lightweight editorial layer gives a path toward downstream editing without turning V1 into a fully editorial grammar.\\n\\n### 9.3 Stronger long-term scalability\\nD is more likely to age well as the system becomes more sophisticated.\\n\\n### 9.4 Still simple enough for V1\\nAs long as the editorial layer remains light, D does not appear too heavy for V1.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 10. What should remain out of scope for V1\\n\\nV1 should not yet include:\\n- detailed sub-taxonomies for every family type\\n- complex timing grammars\\n- fine-grained motion strategy per family authored by the LLM\\n- deep scene-to-scene editorial logic\\n- asset scoring theory inside the grammar itself\\n\\nThose can be added later if real downstream consumers demand them.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 11. Summary\\n\\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\\n\\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\\n\\nThis grammar is preferred because it:\\n- preserves factual grounding where needed\\n- supports controlled creative freedom\\n- helps S6 materialize useful kits\\n- gives S7 a better editorial bridge\\n- remains implementable in V1\\n\\nA further V1 simplification also applies:\\n- motion should not be decided freely by the S5 LLM\\n- the preferred policy is `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically into the scene context\\n\\nThis keeps the grammar strong without making it unnecessarily complicated.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1383,"output":3250,"cacheRead":111104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":115737,"cost":{"input":0.0034575,"output":0.04875,"cacheRead":0.027776,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0799835}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775557465968,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4db5cffe08196b492cb123003edcb"}}
