{"type":"message","id":"c3435349","parentId":"1ab7f5f9","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:35:40.314Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_bLux2dbd7WnmbsDxZqdYa7RZ|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4dde01a0c81968b46291d9c6d4cb7","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"edit\",\n  \"error\": \"Could not find edits[1] in C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md. The oldText must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines.\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"edit","error":"Could not find edits[1] in C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md. The oldText must match exactly including all whitespace and newlines."},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775558140278}}
{"type":"message","id":"9f7998d8","parentId":"c3435349","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:35:46.145Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fbMgcVVZtAzqvAAlALGybM5b|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de035bd08196b23e163c8a1ba13f","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md","offset":70,"limit":220},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md\",\"offset\":70,\"limit\":220}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":124989,"output":61,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125050,"cost":{"input":0.31247250000000004,"output":0.000915,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.31338750000000004}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775558140316,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4ddff5bc4819689531173496d194c"}}
{"type":"message","id":"0abb0305","parentId":"9f7998d8","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:35:46.514Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fbMgcVVZtAzqvAAlALGybM5b|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de035bd08196b23e163c8a1ba13f","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n---\n\n## 4. Preferred direction for V1\n\nThe current preferred direction is:\n\n## Option D — two-layer grammar (contained V1 version)\n\nThis means each asset family should contain:\n\n### Layer 1 — production-facing fields\nThese fields are primarily for S5→S6 communication.\nThey define what kind of family this is, how important it is, how grounded it must be, and how it should be materialized.\n\n### Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\nThese fields provide minimal downstream usefulness for S7 without turning V1 into a full editorial grammar.\n\nThis split is attractive because it:\n- keeps S6-facing structure clear\n- preserves a future bridge into S7\n- avoids overloading one field with both production and editorial semantics\n- remains simpler than a fully editorial-first model\n\n---\n\n## 5. Core V1 principle: factual grounding is not optional in factual scenes\n\nA crucial rule must be explicit in this grammar:\n\n> when a scene depicts a real and identifiable person, place, building, city, object, weapon, vehicle, aircraft, artifact, or other factual element, the correct S4 references must be used as grounding inputs for generation.\n\nThis is not a stylistic preference.\nIt is a structural correctness requirement.\n\nThe reason is practical and proven:\n- if the visuals drift away from the real referent\n- viewers notice\n- comments call out the inaccuracy\n- trust degrades\n\nThat means V1 grammar must make room for:\n- `reference_inputs[]`\n- `preserve_requirements[]`\n- grounding strength\n- clear constraints against generic drift\n\nThese fields are not decorative.\nThey are central to the system’s factual integrity.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Proposed V1 grammar\n\nEach `asset_family` should have the following structure.\n\n---\n\n## 6.1 Layer 1 — production-facing fields\n\n### `family_id`\nStable identifier within the scene kit.\n\n### `family_type`\nThe broad type of material this family represents.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `hero`\n- `support`\n- `detail`\n- `atmospheric`\n- `transition`\n- `fallback`\n\nThese values are intentionally modest.\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\n\n### `priority`\nHow important this family is to the scene.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `required`\n- `preferred`\n- `optional`\n\n### `target_asset_count`\nHow many assets this family should ideally yield.\n\nSuggested shape:\n- `minimum`\n- `ideal`\n- `maximum`\n\n### `grounding_strength`\nHow strongly the family must remain anchored to the factual world of the scene.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `high`\n- `medium`\n- `low`\n\n### `creative_freedom_level`\nHow much interpretive freedom S6 may use when materializing this family.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `strict`\n- `controlled`\n- `moderate`\n- `open`\n\n### `preferred_generation_modes[]`\nWhich generation modes best fit this family.\n\nProposed V1 examples:\n- `reference_guided_generation`\n- `regeneration_from_reference`\n- `from_scratch_generation`\n- `multi_reference_synthesis`\n- `motion_generation`\n\nThese should remain under the limits of the active video-level generation policy.\n\n### `reference_inputs[]`\nThe references from S4 or derived reference packages that should feed this family.\n\nThis field is especially important in factual scenes.\n\n### `preserve_requirements[]`\nA short list of what must remain accurate or legible if this family is generated from references.\n\nExamples:\n- facial identity\n- building silhouette\n- vehicle profile\n- object shape\n- period-accurate details\n\n### `avoid_literal_copy_notes[]`\nWhat should explicitly not be copied literally from the references.\n\nExamples:\n- exact source framing\n- source watermark-bearing composition\n- directly recognizable copyrighted layout\n- source-specific visual signature\n\n### `family_notes`\nShort explanatory note for cases where the structured fields are insufficient.\n\n---\n\n## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\n\n### `editorial_affordance`\nA lightweight indicator of how this family is likely to help downstream editorial work.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `hold`\n- `insert`\n- `sequence`\n- `bridge`\n- `contrast`\n\nThese values are intentionally light.\nThey are not a full editorial grammar.\nThey only provide enough signal to help downstream thinking.\n\n### `editorial_notes`\nShort free-text note on how the family is likely to be useful in the cut.\n\nThis is preferable to adding many more enums too early.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Motion simplification for V1\n\nV1 should avoid making motion a free design variable at the LLM level.\n\n### 7.1 Current preferred policy\nThe preferred system-level rule is:\n\n- `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\n- scenes with index `<= 10` receive `motion_allowed = true`\n- scenes after that receive `motion_allowed = false`\n\n### 7.2 Important consequence\nThis means:\n- the S5 LLM does **not** decide motion from scratch\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically by the substrate or boundary logic\n- families may still prefer `motion_generation` only if the policy allows it for that scene\n\n### 7.3 Why this simplification is good\nIt reduces:\n- complexity\n- inconsistency\n- cost explosion\n- unnecessary planner burden\n\nwhile still enabling motion where the system most wants it.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Worked examples\n\nThe examples below are intentionally concrete because the grammar only becomes understandable when seen under real scene conditions.\n\n---\n\n## 8.1 Real person scene\n\n### Scene\nGeorge S. Patton is introduced as the commanding force of an offensive.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f1\nfamily_type: hero\npriority: required\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n\n[188 more lines in file. Use offset=290 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775558146475}}
{"type":"message","id":"301b0400","parentId":"0abb0305","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:35:51.514Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7J8Na8K2NdOfBDW8nRLJfJIp|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de08a4bc819699e7ecc9e4c03f22","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md","offset":290,"limit":220},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md\",\"offset\":290,\"limit\":220}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":126281,"output":61,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126342,"cost":{"input":0.31570250000000005,"output":0.000915,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.31661750000000005}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775558146517,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de051ce08196b05b442beee40708"}}
{"type":"message","id":"91c3c186","parentId":"301b0400","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:35:51.865Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_7J8Na8K2NdOfBDW8nRLJfJIp|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de08a4bc819699e7ecc9e4c03f22","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 2\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\n  - regeneration_from_reference\nreference_inputs:\n  - patton_face_reference_01\n  - patton_uniform_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - facial identity of George S. Patton\n  - correct military uniform cues\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid exact source framing\neditorial_affordance: hold\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt tells S6 very clearly:\n- who the scene must show\n- what cannot drift\n- how free the generation may be\n- what editorial role the output is likely to serve\n\n---\n\n## 8.2 Real building / place scene\n\n### Scene\nHotel Quitandinha appears as a symbol of scale, prestige, and national ambition.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f2\nfamily_type: support\npriority: preferred\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 2\n  ideal: 3\n  maximum: 4\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\nreference_inputs:\n  - quitandinha_facade_01\n  - quitandinha_architecture_detail_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - recognizable Hotel Quitandinha architecture\n  - key facade and structure cues\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\neditorial_affordance: sequence\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nThe family remains grounded in the correct building while still supporting editorial richness.\n\n---\n\n## 8.3 Real equipment / vehicle scene\n\n### Scene\nA Tiger I tank is described as a symbol of German armored power.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f3\nfamily_type: detail\npriority: preferred\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 3\ngrounding_strength: high\ncreative_freedom_level: controlled\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - reference_guided_generation\nreference_inputs:\n  - tiger1_profile_01\n  - tiger1_turret_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - Tiger I silhouette\n  - correct turret/body structure\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\neditorial_affordance: insert\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt directly encodes the rule that the system must not drift into generic vehicles when factual specificity is essential.\n\n---\n\n## 8.4 Symbolic / evocative scene\n\n### Scene\nAn empire is described as rotting from within.\n\n### Example family\n```yaml\nfamily_id: f4\nfamily_type: atmospheric\npriority: required\ntarget_asset_count:\n  minimum: 1\n  ideal: 2\n  maximum: 3\ngrounding_strength: low\ncreative_freedom_level: open\npreferred_generation_modes:\n  - from_scratch_generation\n  - multi_reference_synthesis\nreference_inputs:\n  - imperial_hall_reference_01\n  - decay_texture_reference_02\npreserve_requirements:\n  - tonal coherence with the rest of the video\navoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\neditorial_affordance: contrast\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\n```\n\n### Why this works\nIt shows that the same grammar can support scenes where factual identity is less rigid while still preserving coherence.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Why Option D is preferred over Option B\n\nOption B remains a respectable alternative, but the current preference for D is based on the following advantages.\n\n### 9.1 Cleaner separation of concerns\nD separates:\n- what S6 must produce\n- how the family may be useful editorially\n\nThis is better than overloading one role/function pair with both meanings.\n\n### 9.2 Better future bridge into S7\nThe lightweight editorial layer gives a path toward downstream editing without turning V1 into a fully editorial grammar.\n\n### 9.3 Stronger long-term scalability\nD is more likely to age well as the system becomes more sophisticated.\n\n### 9.4 Still simple enough for V1\nAs long as the editorial layer remains light, D does not appear too heavy for V1.\n\n---\n\n## 10. What should remain out of scope for V1\n\nV1 should not yet include:\n- detailed sub-taxonomies for every family type\n- complex timing grammars\n- fine-grained motion strategy per family authored by the LLM\n- deep scene-to-scene editorial logic\n- asset scoring theory inside the grammar itself\n\nThose can be added later if real downstream consumers demand them.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Summary\n\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\n\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\n\nThis grammar is preferred because it:\n- preserves factual grounding where needed\n- supports controlled creative freedom\n- helps S6 materialize useful kits\n- gives S7 a better editorial bridge\n- remains implementable in V1\n\nA further V1 simplification also applies:\n- motion should not be decided freely by the S5 LLM\n- the preferred policy is `motion_policy: first_10_scenes_only`\n- `motion_allowed` should be injected deterministically into the scene context\n\nThis keeps the grammar strong without making it unnecessarily complicated.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1775558151830}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e15b674","parentId":"91c3c186","timestamp":"2026-04-07T10:36:09.990Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_DpMPNoiSfpmwEkEXdxMc9Qeh|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de0ba014819680f905664544c258","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md","edits":[{"oldText":"These values are intentionally modest.\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\n","newText":"These values are intentionally modest.\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\nThey also replace the need for a second competing family-role taxonomy in V1.\n"},{"oldText":"## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\n\n### `editorial_affordance`\nA lightweight indicator of how this family is likely to help downstream editorial work.\n\nProposed V1 values:\n- `hold`\n- `insert`\n- `sequence`\n- `bridge`\n- `contrast`\n\nThese values are intentionally light.\nThey are not a full editorial grammar.\nThey only provide enough signal to help downstream thinking.\n\n### `editorial_notes`\nShort free-text note on how the family is likely to be useful in the cut.\n\nThis is preferable to adding many more enums too early.\n","newText":"## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\n\n### `editorial_notes`\nA lightweight free-text note on how this family is likely to be useful in the cut.\n\nIn the current preferred V1 direction, the editorial layer should remain textual rather than enum-heavy.\nThat means:\n- no separate closed editorial role taxonomy is required yet\n- no heavy editorial affordance system is required yet\n- the family keeps its production-facing `family_type`\n- downstream/editorial nuance is expressed through concise text\n\nThis is preferable in V1 because it is:\n- easier for LLMs to generate naturally\n- easier to interpret in context\n- less brittle than forcing prematurely rigid editorial enums\n"},{"oldText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid exact source framing\neditorial_affordance: hold\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene.\n```","newText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid exact source framing\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene; should sustain an opening or emphasis beat.\n```"},{"oldText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\neditorial_affordance: sequence\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\n```","newText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\n```"},{"oldText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\neditorial_affordance: insert\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\n```","newText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\n```"},{"oldText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\neditorial_affordance: contrast\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\n```","newText":"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\n```"},{"oldText":"## 11. Summary\n\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\n\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\n","newText":"## 10.5 Additional stress-test examples still recommended\n\nThe current examples already cover an important spectrum, but before freezing the grammar more strongly it is still recommended to add at least:\n- a transition-oriented scene example\n- a person + location simultaneous scene example\n\nThese two cases are especially important because they are common in real videos and stress-test whether one family grammar can handle multiple factual anchors and editorial bridging needs at once.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Summary\n\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\n\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\n"}]},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_ASSET_FAMILY_GRAMMAR_V1_DRAFT.md\",\"edits\":[{\"oldText\":\"These values are intentionally modest.\\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\\n\",\"newText\":\"These values are intentionally modest.\\nThey are expressive enough for V1 without becoming taxonomically heavy.\\nThey also replace the need for a second competing family-role taxonomy in V1.\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\\n\\n### `editorial_affordance`\\nA lightweight indicator of how this family is likely to help downstream editorial work.\\n\\nProposed V1 values:\\n- `hold`\\n- `insert`\\n- `sequence`\\n- `bridge`\\n- `contrast`\\n\\nThese values are intentionally light.\\nThey are not a full editorial grammar.\\nThey only provide enough signal to help downstream thinking.\\n\\n### `editorial_notes`\\nShort free-text note on how the family is likely to be useful in the cut.\\n\\nThis is preferable to adding many more enums too early.\\n\",\"newText\":\"## 6.2 Layer 2 — lightweight editorial-facing fields\\n\\n### `editorial_notes`\\nA lightweight free-text note on how this family is likely to be useful in the cut.\\n\\nIn the current preferred V1 direction, the editorial layer should remain textual rather than enum-heavy.\\nThat means:\\n- no separate closed editorial role taxonomy is required yet\\n- no heavy editorial affordance system is required yet\\n- the family keeps its production-facing `family_type`\\n- downstream/editorial nuance is expressed through concise text\\n\\nThis is preferable in V1 because it is:\\n- easier for LLMs to generate naturally\\n- easier to interpret in context\\n- less brittle than forcing prematurely rigid editorial enums\\n\"},{\"oldText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid exact source framing\\neditorial_affordance: hold\\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene.\\n```\",\"newText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid exact source framing\\neditorial_notes: Primary identity anchor for the scene; should sustain an opening or emphasis beat.\\n```\"},{\"oldText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\\neditorial_affordance: sequence\\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\\n```\",\"newText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid repetitive angle duplication\\neditorial_notes: Support progression from grounded establishing into richer architectural coverage.\\n```\"},{\"oldText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\\neditorial_affordance: insert\\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\\n```\",\"newText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid genericizing into an unspecified tank\\neditorial_notes: Factual machine-specific reinforcement.\\n```\"},{\"oldText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\\neditorial_affordance: contrast\\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\\n```\",\"newText\":\"avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n  - avoid heavy-handed symbolic cliché\\neditorial_notes: Symbolic emotional expansion of the scene.\\n```\"},{\"oldText\":\"## 11. Summary\\n\\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\\n\\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\\n\",\"newText\":\"## 10.5 Additional stress-test examples still recommended\\n\\nThe current examples already cover an important spectrum, but before freezing the grammar more strongly it is still recommended to add at least:\\n- a transition-oriented scene example\\n- a person + location simultaneous scene example\\n\\nThese two cases are especially important because they are common in real videos and stress-test whether one family grammar can handle multiple factual anchors and editorial bridging needs at once.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 11. Summary\\n\\nThe preferred V1 grammar for `asset_families[]` is now:\\n\\n> Option D — a two-layer grammar with a strong production-facing layer and a lightweight editorial-facing layer.\\n\"}]}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1309,"output":915,"cacheRead":126208,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128432,"cost":{"input":0.0032725000000000002,"output":0.013725000000000001,"cacheRead":0.031552,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.048549499999999995}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775558151867,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d4de0a74f48196baef20d948447097"}}
