{"type":"message","id":"085f5b38","parentId":"e81467b9","timestamp":"2026-04-07T13:30:55.474Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-04-07 10:30 GMT-3] A)\ndocumentar estes dois mocks compactos como exemplos oficiais do S5\n\nB)\nsubir mais um nível e documentar a shape canónica do scene_kit_spec V1, usando estes exemplos como prova\n\né entao kkk, o B é o A melhorado. Sim monta isso"}],"timestamp":1775568655433}}
{"type":"message","id":"6a642db0","parentId":"085f5b38","timestamp":"2026-04-07T13:32:18.554Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_HxeCAA52lTamgVCB7hNaCm7T|fc_06eabf5088e8d8890169d50719035081969473618e41e3dc69","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\OpenClaw Workspace\\content_factory_block2\\S5\\S5_SCENE_KIT_SPEC_V1_DRAFT.md","content":"# S5 Scene Kit Spec V1 Draft\n\n_Status: conceptual output draft_  \n_Last updated: 2026-04-07_  \n_Owner: Tobias_\n\n---\n\n## 1. Purpose of this document\n\nThis document defines the **draft canonical V1 shape** of the `scene_kit_spec` artifact that S5 should produce per scene.\n\nIts purpose is to convert the S5 design work into a practical scene-level output structure that can:\n- be authored from the real S5 input assembly layer\n- communicate scene-kit intent clearly to S6\n- avoid over-closing the final composition of the scene\n- remain compact enough for V1\n- still preserve enough structure to support real downstream editorial freedom later\n\nThis document is not yet a final JSON schema freeze.\nIt is the practical shape draft that the system can now think with consistently.\n\n---\n\n## 2. What this artifact is\n\nA `scene_kit_spec` is the scene-level output of S5.\n\nIt is the artifact through which S5 says:\n- what this scene needs visually\n- what the scene is really about\n- what factual anchors must remain grounded\n- what kinds of asset families S6 must materialize\n- what minimum delivery must exist for the scene to remain editable downstream\n\nIt is **not**:\n- the final scene composition\n- the final editing plan\n- a rigid shot list\n- a single prompt per scene\n\nIt is a scene-level specification of the **asset space** the scene needs.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Design principles for the V1 shape\n\n### 3.1 Keep it compact but serious\nV1 should avoid excessive richness while still being strong enough for real S6 consumption.\n\n### 3.2 Preserve the difference between interpretation and instruction\nThe spec should contain:\n- enough scene reading for the kit to make sense\n- enough concrete family instructions for S6 to act\n\n### 3.3 Do not confuse scene kit with final composition\nThe spec should define what the scene must have available, not how the final scene must be composed on screen.\n\n### 3.4 Preserve factual integrity where necessary\nWhen the scene includes real people, places, objects, vehicles, weapons, buildings, or artifacts, the spec must ensure that the correct references are used and preserved appropriately.\n\n### 3.5 Support both grounded and symbolic scenes\nThe shape must remain viable for:\n- highly factual scenes\n- relational scenes\n- partly symbolic scenes\n- transition-oriented scenes\n\n---\n\n## 4. Canonical V1 shape\n\nThe current draft shape of `scene_kit_spec` is:\n\n### A. `scene_core`\nBasic identity and narrative normalization for the scene.\n\nFields:\n- `scene_text`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `sequence_position`\n\n### B. `scene_direction`\nShort, high-value reading of what the scene must communicate and what kind of scene it is.\n\nFields:\n- `scene_thesis`\n- `factual_anchors[]`\n- `thematic_layer[]`\n- `dominant_scene_mode`\n\n### C. `applied_global_constraints`\nThe subset of the global direction frame that materially matters to this scene.\n\nFields:\n- `dominant_visual_era`\n- `dominant_style_mode`\n- `grounding_baseline`\n- `motion_allowed`\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\n\n### D. `kit_strategy`\nThe scene-level statement of what the kit is trying to enable.\n\nFields:\n- `kit_goal`\n- `kit_size_target`\n  - `minimum`\n  - `ideal`\n  - `maximum`\n\n### E. `asset_families[]`\nThe core production-facing scene-kit content.\n\nEach family contains:\n- `family_id`\n- `family_type`\n- `family_intent`\n- `priority`\n- `target_asset_count`\n  - `minimum`\n  - `ideal`\n  - `maximum`\n- `grounding_strength`\n- `creative_freedom_level`\n- `preferred_generation_modes[]`\n- `reference_inputs[]`\n- `preserve_requirements[]`\n- `avoid_literal_copy_notes[]`\n- `editorial_notes`\n\n### F. `delivery_expectations`\nThe minimum and preferred delivery conditions S6 should aim to satisfy.\n\nFields:\n- `minimum_viable_delivery[]`\n- `preferred_enrichment[]`\n\n---\n\n## 5. Why this shape is preferred\n\nThis shape is preferred because it provides six important properties at once.\n\n### 5.1 It is compact enough for V1\nIt avoids excessive explanatory sprawl.\n\n### 5.2 It preserves a real scene reading layer\nS5 is not reduced to blindly emitting families without understanding the scene.\n\n### 5.3 It is actionable for S6\nFamilies are concrete enough to drive materialization.\n\n### 5.4 It preserves editorial openness for S7\nIt defines the asset space without freezing final composition.\n\n### 5.5 It supports grounded factual scenes\nIt handles people, places, architecture, and object identity correctly.\n\n### 5.6 It also supports symbolic or mixed scenes\nIt remains usable when scenes need mood, decay, interpretation, or transition rather than only strict factual depiction.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The role of `family_type + family_intent`\n\nOne of the most important conclusions of the S5 design work is that:\n\n> `family_type` alone is too vague.\n\nBroad labels such as:\n- `hero`\n- `support`\n- `detail`\n- `atmospheric`\n- `transition`\n- `fallback`\n\nare useful categories, but they do not tell S6 enough unless the family also states its concrete mission.\n\nThat is why the production-facing language of the family in V1 must be:\n- `family_type`\n- `family_intent`\n\nThis combination is what makes the scene-kit structure concrete without over-fragmenting the taxonomy.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Example A — relational factual scene\n\n### Scene\n“Joaquim Rolla sonhava transformar o Hotel Quitandinha no maior cassino do mundo.”\n\n### Compact `scene_kit_spec` example\n\n```yaml\nscene_kit_spec:\n  spec_version: v1_draft\n  scene_id: scene_016\n\n  scene_core:\n    scene_text: \"Joaquim Rolla sonhava transformar o Hotel Quitandinha no maior cassino do mundo.\"\n    scene_summary: \"The scene introduces Joaquim Rolla's ambition to turn Hotel Quitandinha into the world's largest casino.\"\n    narrative_function: \"introduce the human visionary and the scale of the project\"\n    sequence_position: 16\n\n  scene_direction:\n    scene_thesis: \"This scene must communicate that Rolla is the human driver of a grand casino ambition attached to the real Hotel Quitandinha.\"\n    factual_anchors:\n      - Joaquim Rolla\n      - Hotel Quitandinha\n    thematic_layer:\n      - casino ambition\n    dominant_scene_mode: factual_plus_cinematic\n\n  applied_global_constraints:\n    dominant_visual_era: \"1940-1946\"\n    dominant_style_mode: documentary_hybrid\n    grounding_baseline: high\n    motion_allowed: false\n    kit_complexity_ceiling: medium\n\n  kit_strategy:\n    kit_goal: \"Provide enough grounded and expressive material for a relational scene centered on Rolla, the hotel, and the casino ambition.\"\n    kit_size_target:\n      minimum: 4\n      ideal: 6\n      maximum: 8\n\n  asset_families:\n    - family_id: f1\n      family_type: hero\n      family_intent: \"Identify Joaquim Rolla as the visionary human agent behind the project.\"\n      priority: required\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 2\n        maximum: 2\n      grounding_strength: high\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - reference_guided_generation\n        - regeneration_from_reference\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_rolla_01\n          source_target_id: t002\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - facial identity of Joaquim Rolla\n        - period-compatible appearance\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not produce a generic elegant businessman\n      editorial_notes: \"Human anchor of the scene.\"\n\n    - family_id: f2\n      family_type: support\n      family_intent: \"Establish Hotel Quitandinha as the real architectural object of Rolla's ambition.\"\n      priority: required\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 2\n        maximum: 3\n      grounding_strength: high\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - reference_guided_generation\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\n          source_target_id: t009\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_04\n          source_target_id: t009\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - recognizable Hotel Quitandinha silhouette\n        - architectural identity\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not collapse into a generic grand hotel\n      editorial_notes: \"Primary place anchor of the scene.\"\n\n    - family_id: f3\n      family_type: detail\n      family_intent: \"Reinforce the casino and luxury identity of what the project was meant to become.\"\n      priority: preferred\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 2\n        maximum: 3\n      grounding_strength: medium\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - reference_guided_generation\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\n          source_target_id: t013\n        - asset_id: a_casino_02\n          source_target_id: t013\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - clear casino/luxury cues\n        - coherence with Quitandinha project context\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not become generic luxury décor\n      editorial_notes: \"Project-destination reinforcement.\"\n\n    - family_id: f4\n      family_type: atmospheric\n      family_intent: \"Elevate the ambition of the project with controlled cinematic grandeur while preserving factual anchors.\"\n      priority: optional\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 1\n        maximum: 2\n      grounding_strength: medium\n      creative_freedom_level: moderate\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n        - from_scratch_generation\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\n          source_target_id: t009\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\n          source_target_id: t013\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - keep the scene tied to Rolla + Quitandinha project\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not drift into fantasy architecture\n      editorial_notes: \"Optional grandeur/elevation layer.\"\n\n  delivery_expectations:\n    minimum_viable_delivery:\n      - one strong Rolla asset\n      - one strong recognizably Quitandinha asset\n      - one useful casino/luxury reinforcing asset\n    preferred_enrichment:\n      - multiple usable framings for Rolla and Quitandinha\n      - at least one elevated/cinematic variant if grounding remains legible\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Example B — symbolic grounded scene\n\n### Scene\n“O império do jogo começava a apodrecer antes mesmo de florescer.”\n\n### Compact `scene_kit_spec` example\n\n```yaml\nscene_kit_spec:\n  spec_version: v1_draft\n  scene_id: scene_symbolic_01\n\n  scene_core:\n    scene_text: \"O império do jogo começava a apodrecer antes mesmo de florescer.\"\n    scene_summary: \"The scene introduces the idea that the gambling empire was already decaying before it fully matured.\"\n    narrative_function: \"shift from factual exposition into symbolic decline and thematic foreshadowing\"\n    sequence_position: 27\n\n  scene_direction:\n    scene_thesis: \"This scene must communicate decay, instability, and collapse-in-advance while remaining tied to the grounded world of the hotel/casino project.\"\n    factual_anchors:\n      - Hotel Quitandinha project world\n      - gambling/casino universe\n    thematic_layer:\n      - decay\n      - premature collapse\n      - grandeur rotting from within\n    dominant_scene_mode: symbolic_grounded\n\n  applied_global_constraints:\n    dominant_visual_era: \"1940-1946\"\n    dominant_style_mode: documentary_hybrid\n    grounding_baseline: high\n    motion_allowed: false\n    kit_complexity_ceiling: medium\n\n  kit_strategy:\n    kit_goal: \"Provide enough evocative and grounded material for a symbolic scene that still belongs to the same factual video world.\"\n    kit_size_target:\n      minimum: 3\n      ideal: 4\n      maximum: 6\n\n  asset_families:\n    - family_id: f1\n      family_type: atmospheric\n      family_intent: \"Create the emotional and symbolic visual field of decay, rot, and instability around the gambling empire.\"\n      priority: required\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 2\n        maximum: 3\n      grounding_strength: low\n      creative_freedom_level: open\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - from_scratch_generation\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\n          source_target_id: t013\n        - asset_id: a_hotel_interior_03\n          source_target_id: t009\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - tonal coherence with the project world\n        - visual relation to luxury/casino/hotel environment\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not become generic dark symbolism\n        - do not sever connection to the video's grounded world\n      editorial_notes: \"Primary symbolic/emotional carrier of the scene.\"\n\n    - family_id: f2\n      family_type: support\n      family_intent: \"Keep the scene visually tied to the real hotel/casino project so the symbolic layer does not float away from the narrative world.\"\n      priority: required\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 1\n        maximum: 2\n      grounding_strength: medium\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - reference_guided_generation\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\n          source_target_id: t009\n        - asset_id: a_casino_02\n          source_target_id: t013\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - recognizability of project/hotel/casino world\n        - continuity with previous factual scenes\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not become generic luxury imagery\n        - do not over-literalize decline in a way that breaks historical coherence\n      editorial_notes: \"Grounding tether for the symbolic layer.\"\n\n    - family_id: f3\n      family_type: transition\n      family_intent: \"Provide bridge material between the factual casino-world exposition and the more interpretive mood of decline.\"\n      priority: optional\n      target_asset_count:\n        minimum: 1\n        ideal: 1\n        maximum: 2\n      grounding_strength: medium\n      creative_freedom_level: moderate\n      preferred_generation_modes:\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\n        - reference_guided_generation\n      reference_inputs:\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\n          source_target_id: t013\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_04\n          source_target_id: t009\n      preserve_requirements:\n        - maintain visual continuity with the factual world\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\n        - do not make the bridge feel like an unrelated visual detour\n      editorial_notes: \"Useful when the editor needs to turn the viewer from explanation into foreboding mood.\"\n\n  delivery_expectations:\n    minimum_viable_delivery:\n      - one strong symbolic/atmospheric asset tied to the casino-hotel world\n      - one grounded support asset that keeps the scene recognizably inside the Quitandinha project universe\n    preferred_enrichment:\n      - more than one atmospheric variation\n      - one useful bridge asset between factual world and symbolic decay\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. What these two examples prove\n\nThese two compact examples demonstrate that the same V1 shape can support materially different scene types:\n\n### Example A proves the shape can handle:\n- relational factual scenes\n- two-anchor scenes\n- strong grounding requirements\n- project/ambition framing\n\n### Example B proves the shape can handle:\n- symbolic scenes\n- grounded-yet-interpretive scenes\n- scenes without a dominant human anchor\n- scenes that need tethering rather than strict literal resolution\n\nThis is an important validation of the compact V1 shape.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Why the compact V1 shape is preferred over the richer exploratory shape\n\nA richer exploratory version of the scene kit spec was useful during design.\nHowever, the compact version is preferred for V1 because it:\n- reduces output verbosity\n- lowers cognitive overhead\n- reduces inconsistency risk\n- remains highly actionable for S6\n- still preserves the distinction between:\n  - scene reading\n  - family-level instruction\n  - delivery expectation\n\nThis is the right tradeoff for a first operational version.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Remaining open questions\n\nThis draft does not yet freeze:\n- final JSON schema\n- exact enum list for every field\n- whether additional compact fields should exist for risk handling\n- whether scene-level secondary fields should be added later\n- exact runtime implementation path for S5\n\nThose should come only after the team is satisfied that this compact shape is the right output target.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Summary\n\nThe current preferred V1 output shape for S5 is a compact `scene_kit_spec` that includes:\n- scene identity and normalized scene reading\n- scene-level direction and anchors\n- applied global constraints\n- kit strategy\n- family-level kit instructions via `asset_families[]`\n- delivery expectations for S6\n\nThis shape is now considered strong enough to support both:\n- grounded factual scenes\n- grounded symbolic scenes\n\nwithout collapsing into either under-specification or premature editorial over-control.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\OpenClaw Workspace\\\\content_factory_block2\\\\S5\\\\S5_SCENE_KIT_SPEC_V1_DRAFT.md\",\"content\":\"# S5 Scene Kit Spec V1 Draft\\n\\n_Status: conceptual output draft_  \\n_Last updated: 2026-04-07_  \\n_Owner: Tobias_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Purpose of this document\\n\\nThis document defines the **draft canonical V1 shape** of the `scene_kit_spec` artifact that S5 should produce per scene.\\n\\nIts purpose is to convert the S5 design work into a practical scene-level output structure that can:\\n- be authored from the real S5 input assembly layer\\n- communicate scene-kit intent clearly to S6\\n- avoid over-closing the final composition of the scene\\n- remain compact enough for V1\\n- still preserve enough structure to support real downstream editorial freedom later\\n\\nThis document is not yet a final JSON schema freeze.\\nIt is the practical shape draft that the system can now think with consistently.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. What this artifact is\\n\\nA `scene_kit_spec` is the scene-level output of S5.\\n\\nIt is the artifact through which S5 says:\\n- what this scene needs visually\\n- what the scene is really about\\n- what factual anchors must remain grounded\\n- what kinds of asset families S6 must materialize\\n- what minimum delivery must exist for the scene to remain editable downstream\\n\\nIt is **not**:\\n- the final scene composition\\n- the final editing plan\\n- a rigid shot list\\n- a single prompt per scene\\n\\nIt is a scene-level specification of the **asset space** the scene needs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Design principles for the V1 shape\\n\\n### 3.1 Keep it compact but serious\\nV1 should avoid excessive richness while still being strong enough for real S6 consumption.\\n\\n### 3.2 Preserve the difference between interpretation and instruction\\nThe spec should contain:\\n- enough scene reading for the kit to make sense\\n- enough concrete family instructions for S6 to act\\n\\n### 3.3 Do not confuse scene kit with final composition\\nThe spec should define what the scene must have available, not how the final scene must be composed on screen.\\n\\n### 3.4 Preserve factual integrity where necessary\\nWhen the scene includes real people, places, objects, vehicles, weapons, buildings, or artifacts, the spec must ensure that the correct references are used and preserved appropriately.\\n\\n### 3.5 Support both grounded and symbolic scenes\\nThe shape must remain viable for:\\n- highly factual scenes\\n- relational scenes\\n- partly symbolic scenes\\n- transition-oriented scenes\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Canonical V1 shape\\n\\nThe current draft shape of `scene_kit_spec` is:\\n\\n### A. `scene_core`\\nBasic identity and narrative normalization for the scene.\\n\\nFields:\\n- `scene_text`\\n- `scene_summary`\\n- `narrative_function`\\n- `sequence_position`\\n\\n### B. `scene_direction`\\nShort, high-value reading of what the scene must communicate and what kind of scene it is.\\n\\nFields:\\n- `scene_thesis`\\n- `factual_anchors[]`\\n- `thematic_layer[]`\\n- `dominant_scene_mode`\\n\\n### C. `applied_global_constraints`\\nThe subset of the global direction frame that materially matters to this scene.\\n\\nFields:\\n- `dominant_visual_era`\\n- `dominant_style_mode`\\n- `grounding_baseline`\\n- `motion_allowed`\\n- `kit_complexity_ceiling`\\n\\n### D. `kit_strategy`\\nThe scene-level statement of what the kit is trying to enable.\\n\\nFields:\\n- `kit_goal`\\n- `kit_size_target`\\n  - `minimum`\\n  - `ideal`\\n  - `maximum`\\n\\n### E. `asset_families[]`\\nThe core production-facing scene-kit content.\\n\\nEach family contains:\\n- `family_id`\\n- `family_type`\\n- `family_intent`\\n- `priority`\\n- `target_asset_count`\\n  - `minimum`\\n  - `ideal`\\n  - `maximum`\\n- `grounding_strength`\\n- `creative_freedom_level`\\n- `preferred_generation_modes[]`\\n- `reference_inputs[]`\\n- `preserve_requirements[]`\\n- `avoid_literal_copy_notes[]`\\n- `editorial_notes`\\n\\n### F. `delivery_expectations`\\nThe minimum and preferred delivery conditions S6 should aim to satisfy.\\n\\nFields:\\n- `minimum_viable_delivery[]`\\n- `preferred_enrichment[]`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Why this shape is preferred\\n\\nThis shape is preferred because it provides six important properties at once.\\n\\n### 5.1 It is compact enough for V1\\nIt avoids excessive explanatory sprawl.\\n\\n### 5.2 It preserves a real scene reading layer\\nS5 is not reduced to blindly emitting families without understanding the scene.\\n\\n### 5.3 It is actionable for S6\\nFamilies are concrete enough to drive materialization.\\n\\n### 5.4 It preserves editorial openness for S7\\nIt defines the asset space without freezing final composition.\\n\\n### 5.5 It supports grounded factual scenes\\nIt handles people, places, architecture, and object identity correctly.\\n\\n### 5.6 It also supports symbolic or mixed scenes\\nIt remains usable when scenes need mood, decay, interpretation, or transition rather than only strict factual depiction.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. The role of `family_type + family_intent`\\n\\nOne of the most important conclusions of the S5 design work is that:\\n\\n> `family_type` alone is too vague.\\n\\nBroad labels such as:\\n- `hero`\\n- `support`\\n- `detail`\\n- `atmospheric`\\n- `transition`\\n- `fallback`\\n\\nare useful categories, but they do not tell S6 enough unless the family also states its concrete mission.\\n\\nThat is why the production-facing language of the family in V1 must be:\\n- `family_type`\\n- `family_intent`\\n\\nThis combination is what makes the scene-kit structure concrete without over-fragmenting the taxonomy.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7. Example A — relational factual scene\\n\\n### Scene\\n“Joaquim Rolla sonhava transformar o Hotel Quitandinha no maior cassino do mundo.”\\n\\n### Compact `scene_kit_spec` example\\n\\n```yaml\\nscene_kit_spec:\\n  spec_version: v1_draft\\n  scene_id: scene_016\\n\\n  scene_core:\\n    scene_text: \\\"Joaquim Rolla sonhava transformar o Hotel Quitandinha no maior cassino do mundo.\\\"\\n    scene_summary: \\\"The scene introduces Joaquim Rolla's ambition to turn Hotel Quitandinha into the world's largest casino.\\\"\\n    narrative_function: \\\"introduce the human visionary and the scale of the project\\\"\\n    sequence_position: 16\\n\\n  scene_direction:\\n    scene_thesis: \\\"This scene must communicate that Rolla is the human driver of a grand casino ambition attached to the real Hotel Quitandinha.\\\"\\n    factual_anchors:\\n      - Joaquim Rolla\\n      - Hotel Quitandinha\\n    thematic_layer:\\n      - casino ambition\\n    dominant_scene_mode: factual_plus_cinematic\\n\\n  applied_global_constraints:\\n    dominant_visual_era: \\\"1940-1946\\\"\\n    dominant_style_mode: documentary_hybrid\\n    grounding_baseline: high\\n    motion_allowed: false\\n    kit_complexity_ceiling: medium\\n\\n  kit_strategy:\\n    kit_goal: \\\"Provide enough grounded and expressive material for a relational scene centered on Rolla, the hotel, and the casino ambition.\\\"\\n    kit_size_target:\\n      minimum: 4\\n      ideal: 6\\n      maximum: 8\\n\\n  asset_families:\\n    - family_id: f1\\n      family_type: hero\\n      family_intent: \\\"Identify Joaquim Rolla as the visionary human agent behind the project.\\\"\\n      priority: required\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 2\\n        maximum: 2\\n      grounding_strength: high\\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - reference_guided_generation\\n        - regeneration_from_reference\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_rolla_01\\n          source_target_id: t002\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - facial identity of Joaquim Rolla\\n        - period-compatible appearance\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not produce a generic elegant businessman\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Human anchor of the scene.\\\"\\n\\n    - family_id: f2\\n      family_type: support\\n      family_intent: \\\"Establish Hotel Quitandinha as the real architectural object of Rolla's ambition.\\\"\\n      priority: required\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 2\\n        maximum: 3\\n      grounding_strength: high\\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - reference_guided_generation\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_04\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - recognizable Hotel Quitandinha silhouette\\n        - architectural identity\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not collapse into a generic grand hotel\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Primary place anchor of the scene.\\\"\\n\\n    - family_id: f3\\n      family_type: detail\\n      family_intent: \\\"Reinforce the casino and luxury identity of what the project was meant to become.\\\"\\n      priority: preferred\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 2\\n        maximum: 3\\n      grounding_strength: medium\\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - reference_guided_generation\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_02\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - clear casino/luxury cues\\n        - coherence with Quitandinha project context\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not become generic luxury décor\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Project-destination reinforcement.\\\"\\n\\n    - family_id: f4\\n      family_type: atmospheric\\n      family_intent: \\\"Elevate the ambition of the project with controlled cinematic grandeur while preserving factual anchors.\\\"\\n      priority: optional\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 1\\n        maximum: 2\\n      grounding_strength: medium\\n      creative_freedom_level: moderate\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n        - from_scratch_generation\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - keep the scene tied to Rolla + Quitandinha project\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not drift into fantasy architecture\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Optional grandeur/elevation layer.\\\"\\n\\n  delivery_expectations:\\n    minimum_viable_delivery:\\n      - one strong Rolla asset\\n      - one strong recognizably Quitandinha asset\\n      - one useful casino/luxury reinforcing asset\\n    preferred_enrichment:\\n      - multiple usable framings for Rolla and Quitandinha\\n      - at least one elevated/cinematic variant if grounding remains legible\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8. Example B — symbolic grounded scene\\n\\n### Scene\\n“O império do jogo começava a apodrecer antes mesmo de florescer.”\\n\\n### Compact `scene_kit_spec` example\\n\\n```yaml\\nscene_kit_spec:\\n  spec_version: v1_draft\\n  scene_id: scene_symbolic_01\\n\\n  scene_core:\\n    scene_text: \\\"O império do jogo começava a apodrecer antes mesmo de florescer.\\\"\\n    scene_summary: \\\"The scene introduces the idea that the gambling empire was already decaying before it fully matured.\\\"\\n    narrative_function: \\\"shift from factual exposition into symbolic decline and thematic foreshadowing\\\"\\n    sequence_position: 27\\n\\n  scene_direction:\\n    scene_thesis: \\\"This scene must communicate decay, instability, and collapse-in-advance while remaining tied to the grounded world of the hotel/casino project.\\\"\\n    factual_anchors:\\n      - Hotel Quitandinha project world\\n      - gambling/casino universe\\n    thematic_layer:\\n      - decay\\n      - premature collapse\\n      - grandeur rotting from within\\n    dominant_scene_mode: symbolic_grounded\\n\\n  applied_global_constraints:\\n    dominant_visual_era: \\\"1940-1946\\\"\\n    dominant_style_mode: documentary_hybrid\\n    grounding_baseline: high\\n    motion_allowed: false\\n    kit_complexity_ceiling: medium\\n\\n  kit_strategy:\\n    kit_goal: \\\"Provide enough evocative and grounded material for a symbolic scene that still belongs to the same factual video world.\\\"\\n    kit_size_target:\\n      minimum: 3\\n      ideal: 4\\n      maximum: 6\\n\\n  asset_families:\\n    - family_id: f1\\n      family_type: atmospheric\\n      family_intent: \\\"Create the emotional and symbolic visual field of decay, rot, and instability around the gambling empire.\\\"\\n      priority: required\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 2\\n        maximum: 3\\n      grounding_strength: low\\n      creative_freedom_level: open\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - from_scratch_generation\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n        - asset_id: a_hotel_interior_03\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - tonal coherence with the project world\\n        - visual relation to luxury/casino/hotel environment\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not become generic dark symbolism\\n        - do not sever connection to the video's grounded world\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Primary symbolic/emotional carrier of the scene.\\\"\\n\\n    - family_id: f2\\n      family_type: support\\n      family_intent: \\\"Keep the scene visually tied to the real hotel/casino project so the symbolic layer does not float away from the narrative world.\\\"\\n      priority: required\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 1\\n        maximum: 2\\n      grounding_strength: medium\\n      creative_freedom_level: controlled\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - reference_guided_generation\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_01\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_02\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - recognizability of project/hotel/casino world\\n        - continuity with previous factual scenes\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not become generic luxury imagery\\n        - do not over-literalize decline in a way that breaks historical coherence\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Grounding tether for the symbolic layer.\\\"\\n\\n    - family_id: f3\\n      family_type: transition\\n      family_intent: \\\"Provide bridge material between the factual casino-world exposition and the more interpretive mood of decline.\\\"\\n      priority: optional\\n      target_asset_count:\\n        minimum: 1\\n        ideal: 1\\n        maximum: 2\\n      grounding_strength: medium\\n      creative_freedom_level: moderate\\n      preferred_generation_modes:\\n        - multi_reference_synthesis\\n        - reference_guided_generation\\n      reference_inputs:\\n        - asset_id: a_casino_01\\n          source_target_id: t013\\n        - asset_id: a_quitandinha_04\\n          source_target_id: t009\\n      preserve_requirements:\\n        - maintain visual continuity with the factual world\\n      avoid_literal_copy_notes:\\n        - do not make the bridge feel like an unrelated visual detour\\n      editorial_notes: \\\"Useful when the editor needs to turn the viewer from explanation into foreboding mood.\\\"\\n\\n  delivery_expectations:\\n    minimum_viable_delivery:\\n      - one strong symbolic/atmospheric asset tied to the casino-hotel world\\n      - one grounded support asset that keeps the scene recognizably inside the Quitandinha project universe\\n    preferred_enrichment:\\n      - more than one atmospheric variation\\n      - one useful bridge asset between factual world and symbolic decay\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 9. What these two examples prove\\n\\nThese two compact examples demonstrate that the same V1 shape can support materially different scene types:\\n\\n### Example A proves the shape can handle:\\n- relational factual scenes\\n- two-anchor scenes\\n- strong grounding requirements\\n- project/ambition framing\\n\\n### Example B proves the shape can handle:\\n- symbolic scenes\\n- grounded-yet-interpretive scenes\\n- scenes without a dominant human anchor\\n- scenes that need tethering rather than strict literal resolution\\n\\nThis is an important validation of the compact V1 shape.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 10. Why the compact V1 shape is preferred over the richer exploratory shape\\n\\nA richer exploratory version of the scene kit spec was useful during design.\\nHowever, the compact version is preferred for V1 because it:\\n- reduces output verbosity\\n- lowers cognitive overhead\\n- reduces inconsistency risk\\n- remains highly actionable for S6\\n- still preserves the distinction between:\\n  - scene reading\\n  - family-level instruction\\n  - delivery expectation\\n\\nThis is the right tradeoff for a first operational version.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 11. Remaining open questions\\n\\nThis draft does not yet freeze:\\n- final JSON schema\\n- exact enum list for every field\\n- whether additional compact fields should exist for risk handling\\n- whether scene-level secondary fields should be added later\\n- exact runtime implementation path for S5\\n\\nThose should come only after the team is satisfied that this compact shape is the right output target.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 12. Summary\\n\\nThe current preferred V1 output shape for S5 is a compact `scene_kit_spec` that includes:\\n- scene identity and normalized scene reading\\n- scene-level direction and anchors\\n- applied global constraints\\n- kit strategy\\n- family-level kit instructions via `asset_families[]`\\n- delivery expectations for S6\\n\\nThis shape is now considered strong enough to support both:\\n- grounded factual scenes\\n- grounded symbolic scenes\\n\\nwithout collapsing into either under-specification or premature editorial over-control.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":192287,"output":4198,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":196485,"cost":{"input":0.4807175,"output":0.06297,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.5436875}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775568655465,"responseId":"resp_06eabf5088e8d8890169d50712defc8196aeed01e000bc7376"}}
